<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1545 GMT, July 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said today Russia
will cut the size of the armed forces by 500,000 to 1.2 million by
the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Charles Taylor, Liberia's presidential candidate has
won nearly 66 percent of the 219,754 votes counted so far in
Saturday's election, according to the Independent Elections
Commission (IECOM) today.
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
has temporarily stopped offering help to Cambodia because Hun Sen,
the second prime minister of the country, had rejected the offer,
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said today.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- All the four people aboard a twin-engine aircraft
were killed when the plane crashed into a field and burst into
flames Sunday afternoon near Springfield, southwest Missouri, the
Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Northern Ireland's powerful pro-British Unionist
party leader said today he would seek reassurances from Prime
Minister Tony Blair that the Irish Republican Army would have to
hand over or decommission some weapons at the start of a
substantial negotiation.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian security forces have uncovered a
bomb-making factory in Beit Sahur near Bethlehem, Israel Radio
reported today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
