<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Bids Farewell to Welfare Housing Allocation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- This capital of east China's
Jiangsu Province has promulgated rules to put an end to the
traditional welfare housing allocation system.
</P>
<P>
The new rules stipulate that a new system will be applied to
the allocation of newly-built residences, which mainly focus
on selling publicly-owned housing property instead of renting.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, publicly-owned residences newly built by
government units and departments, social communities, enterprises
and institutions in the city should be sold to their staff members
in line with the housing sales policies contained in the housing
reform package.
</P>
<P>
The rules provide that units may also build houses by raising
their own funds, and these houses will be sold to their employees
at cost price upon completion.
</P>
<P>
Households with annual incomes below 50,000 yuan or average
annual per capita income less than 16,600 yuan are allowed to
apply to purchase houses at cost price.
</P>
<P>
According to a deputy mayor of the city, Nanjing started its
housing reform in 1992, and has now set up a system whereby it
raises public funds for new housing construction. So far, some
125,000 publicly-owned apartments have been sold in line with the
housing reform policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UUP Leader Says Talks with Blair Inconclusive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's Ulster Unionist
Party (UUP) leader David Trimble said today his meeting with Prime
Minister Tony Blair on the surrender of IRA arms was inconclusive
but more efforts would be exerted.
</P>
<P>
Trimble, emerging from a one-and-half hour meeting with Blair
at Downing Street, told reporters: "There are some possibilities
of progress...but the matter is not yet clear."
</P>
<P>
"We will not shirk our responsibilities. We are not in the mode
of walking out. We are there to try to achieve things," the leader
of the most powerful Pro-British Protestant party said.
</P>
<P>
UUP, which wants Northern Ireland to remain under British rule,
are angry at government decision to allow IRA's political wing
Sinn Fein to join the peace talks because the IRA called a truce
at the weekend. The Irish Republican Army has launched military
campaign in the past 28 years to end British rule of Northern
Ireland, costing 3,200 lives.
</P>
<P>
Trimble insists that IRA should hand over weapons at the start
of the negotiation before Sinn Fein is allowed to have a place at
the talks scheduled for mid-September.
</P>
<P>
But Britain's Northern Ireland secretary Mo Mowlam, who was
with Blair at the talks, said Trimble had not threatened to walk
out of the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"There is no indication that the UUP were going to walk from
the talks which is very useful because, after the ceasefire, what
is important to so many people in Northern Ireland is that we do
manage to move the talks process forward," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Trimble will hold another round of talks with British
government officials ahead of a vote on Britain's
"decommissioning" plans on Wednesday at the talks in Belfast
co-sponsored by Britain and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
However, two other pro-British unionist parties, the U.K.
Unionist party and the Democratic Unionist Party, are threatening
to boycotting the talks in protest of British government's "terror
appeasement."
</P>
<P>
Under British proposals the Irish Republican Army and other
guerrilla groups will not have to surrender weapons to gain
representation at the talks but must discuss the issue in a
sub-committee alongside political negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
