<HEADLINE> Senior Pak Diplomat Holds Talks with Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Pakistani diplomat
today resumed his shuttle diplomacy in Afghanistan by holding
talks with the leadership of the Islamic Taliban militia to bring
Afghan warring factions to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Iftikhar Murshed, Pakistan's Additional Foreign Secretary, held
talks today with the Taliban's acting foreign minister Abdul Jalil
and other officials in Kandahar, a major city in southern
Afghanistan, Pakistan Television (PTV) reported.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Murshed briefed the Taliban leaders on his
parleys last week with ousted Afghan president Burhanuddin
Rabbani, Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik and former military chief Ahmad
Masood, who control the northern one-third of the Afghan
territory, PTV said.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed the Taliban leaders on the talks held with
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Alauddin Broujerdi in Islamabad on
Friday, said PTV.
</P>
<P>
During Broujerdi's visit to Pakistan, Tehran and Islamabad
agreed to use their influence to induce the Taliban and the rival
northern alliance to sit together and find a peaceful solution to
the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
In the past weeks, Murshed held talks with the leadership of
the northern alliance in Mazar-e-Sharif, during which all of them
expressed willingness to enter into political dialogue aimed at
bringing peace to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The northern alliance, based in Mazar-e-Sharif, has forwarded
the idea of setting up a joint political commission for a
broad-based government in Afghanistan while the Taliban call for
unconditional release of their senior officials including foreign
minister Mulla Muhammad Ghous as a confidence-building measure for
talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
