<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Calls on Muslims to Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Iranian President Akbar
Hashemi Rafsanjani today called on Muslim countries to get
united to fight against world hegemony.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 10th International Islamic Unity Conference
being held here, Rafsanjani said the Islamic countries have an
important role to play in the world in view of their rich energy
resources and strategic geographical locations in the most
sensitive parts on the globe.
</P>
<P>
"This has prompted the hostility of powerful countries and
made them challenge the Muslim and Islamic governments," said the
64-year-old president who is to step down on August 3 after his
two terms of office.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani called on Islamic countries to use their oil
resources as a rational lever against foreign bullying and drop
the practice of adventurism in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He added that "All Muslims want is to be allowed to live in
peace and freedom from any domination."
</P>
<P>
"The shortest way for Islamic movements to recapture glory and
sovereignty of Islam is the establishment of Islamic system of
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the big powers in the West are working to
promote the idea that Islam lacks the platforms needed for
the establishment of a government.
</P>
<P>
"The driving motive of big powers behind this approach is to
plunder the wealth of the Islamic countries and maintain their
presence in these countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, no contradiction exists between formation
of an Islamic government in Islamic countries and the world of
Christianity and in relations with European countries.
</P>
<P>
About 75 foreign guests from 31 countries and a large number
of scholars attended the three-day conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
