<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Is to Develop More Constructive Relation with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- UK and China relations are now
entering a "new, more positive phase". Britain hopes the two
countries can build on already good relations in the economic and
financial area, said Helen Liddell, Economic Secretary to the
Treasury here today.
</P>
<P>
Delivering her welcoming address at the Regulatory
Familiarization Program For China, the Secretary said: "I am glad
to have this opportunity to talk to regulators and officials who
represent the real links in our financial regulatory relations
with China."
</P>
<P>
Recalling to the significant meeting between Chinese and
British leaders during the ceremony of the handover of Hongkong,
the Secretary said: "It is good that Prime Minister and Foreign
Secretary were able to meet Chinese leaders in Hongkong."
</P>
<P>
"This is an historic occasion, in more than one sense
...This is a new Government at the dawn of developing a more
constructive relationship generally between our two countries,"
Liddell added
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Memorandum of Understanding which the UK
Government signed with the China Securities Regulatory Commission,
Liddell said: "as a direct result of this agreement, this
regulatory familiarization program has been especially put
together to show the Government's commitment to strengthening
links between our two countries in the financial sphere."
</P>
<P>
Looking forward to further cooperation between Britain and
China in economic and financial areas, the Secretary said:
"Agreement on a UK/China Financial Dialogue will be taken forward
when the Chancellor, Gordon Brown, meets the Chinese Minister of
Finance, Liu Zhougli at the International Monetary Fund/World Bank
meeting in Hongkong in September this year."
</P>
<P>
Liddell also said that Britain is delighted that China is now a
member of the International Organization of Security Commissions
and is playing a full and active role, commensurate with her
rapidly expanding financial markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
