<HEADLINE> S.Africa to Host Worldwide Peace Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has been chosen to
host the launch of an international "Peace to the Cities" campaign, an
initiative by the World Council of Churches (WCC), local press
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The launch, scheduled to take place in Johannesburg on August 31,
will see the gathering of world's leading church dignitaries, senior
government officials, diplomats and businessmen, for a global
initiative which recognises the international concern for crime and
violence, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, life President of
the South African Council of Churches, Beyers Naude, said the issue of
violence and crime had become a matter of global concern.
</P>
<P>
Concern for crime and violence should not be limited to protests
but to concrete actions, said Naude.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he stressed that ideas needed to be steered into
positive, concrete and mobile actions in which people could become
involved at grassroots level.
</P>
<P>
Durban is among seven cities chosen by the WCC for the campaign.
The other six are: Rio De Janeiro in Brazil, Belfast in Northern
Ireland, Boston in the United States, Suva in Fiji, Kingston in
Jamaica and Colombo in Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
