<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delay over Euro to Bring Threat of Damages: EU Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior European Commission
official has warned that postponing the introduction of the
European single currency named euro beyond the planned start of
1999 would have serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
Yves-Thibault de Silguy, European Union (EU) Commissioner
responsible for monetary affairs, was quoted by today's Financial
Times as saying that a delay over euro would be a breach of the
1992 Maastricht Treaty for Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
"If the EU heads of government decide that we begin in 2001 or
2002, a flood of damage claims will break over us," de Silguy
said.
</P>
<P>
"All banks, all companies that have put their faith in the
Maastricht Treaty could demand reimbursement of their costs of
preparation for the EMU," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner insisted that Maastricht Treaty did not allow
EMU to be delayed beyond January 1 1999, warning the euro would be
dead because that would require the treaty to be changed and
ratified again by the parliaments of the EU member states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
