<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Pay the Price for New Profits Tax: Employers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- France's national employers'
association the CNPF reacted mildly to the announcement by the
Socialist government to raise 22 billion francs (3.6 billion U.S.
dollars) of profit tax on enterprises in the remaining months of
the year in order to reduce public deficit.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after Finance Minister Dominique
Strauss-Kahn announced the new tax, the CNPF said that not only
the enterprises, but also France itself, will pay the price for
the measure which is aimed at helping the country join the
European single currency by 1999.
</P>
<P>
France's public deficit is expected to stand at 3.5-3.7 percent
of its gross domestic product by the end of 1997, higher than the
three percent criteria set by the Maastricht treaty for joining
the euro.
</P>
<P>
In a symbolic gesture to support the enterprises, President
Jacques Chirac today had dinner together with a number of French
and German entrepreneurs in the Elysee presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
"Once more, France, which keeps the world record of public
taxes, has decided to resolve the difficulties by increasing taxes
and making enterprises bear the bulk of the efforts," said CNPF,
adding that the measure must be "exceptional" and have a
"limited duration."
</P>
<P>
Former Finance Minister and the leader of France's Liberal
Democratic Party, Alain Madelin, described the measure to raise
profit tax as being "against the current of Europe."
</P>
<P>
"In fact, it is not only the rich bosses and great enterprises
which will pay, but also medium-sized enterprises which are
growing, those which can invest, innovate and create jobs," he
said.
</P>
<P>
All French enterprises with 50 million francs (8.3 million U.S.
dollars) of transactions will be covered by the new tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pudong Records Steady Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua/OANA) -- The Pudong New Area in this
leading industrial city of China witnessed steady economic growth
in the first half of this year, with GDP topping 25.692 billion
yuan, up 17.7 percent over same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that compared with the same period of
last year Pudong's industrial output value from January through
June totaled 63.388 billion yuan, up 17.2 percent. The fixed
assets investment stood at 14.734 billion yuan, representing an
increase of 42.8 percent. Meanwhile, the retail sales volume of
consumer commodities rose by 16.2 percent to 7.487 billion
yuan-worth.
</P>
<P>
Progress has also been made in foreign trade, with exports
increasing by 23.3 percent to 1.687 billion US dollars-worth in
the first half of the year, higher than the city's average.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Pudong's average per capita labor productivity has
been enhanced from 24,800 yuan at the beginning of the year to the
present 37,200 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure construction has made great headway; a number of
key projects, including Pudong International Airport, the No.2
Subway Line and municipal public facilities are under way.
</P>
<P>
Significantly, Pudong signed another 313 foreign-funded
projects in the first half of the year, with investment totaling
2.654 billion US dollars, including 749 million US dollars-worth
of foreign funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
