<HEADLINE> China Aims High at America's Cup Yacht Race Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A leading official of China's
water sports announced here today that China would try to send a
yacht to the prestigious America's Cup yacht race sometime early
next century.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qing, director of the Water Sports Administrative Center
of the Chinese State Sports Commission, made the announcement
after the completion of the country's first ever high-sea sailing
regatta South China Sea Sailing Race here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The regatta involved 19 boats -- seven from China's inland
areas and the others from Hong Kong. The 20-day race started on
July 1 at Dalian, a major port city in northeast China's Liaoning
province, and covered some 3,000 nautical miles.
</P>
<P>
Two of the participating boats had to quit mid-way as their
sails were torn to pieces by strong gusts.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first step for the Chinese Yachting Association
towards America's Cup," Zhang said at the awarding ceremony held
at the Hong Kong Yacht Club here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the association would continue its efforts for
entering the world's top-class yacht race.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Chinese yachtsmen have competed in Olympic-class
yacht races, with boats smaller than some of the boats used in the
Dalian-Hong Kong regatta.  
</P>
</TEXT>
