<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Moves Poison Atmosphere: Cypriot President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today rejected Turkish
Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's statement made Sunday on
Turkey's partial integration process with northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides said here that Ecevit's
statement, together with a joint declaration issued Sunday by
Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot regime in the northern Cyprus, will
harm the good climate that has emerged from recent U.N.-sponsored
bi-communal direct talks.
</P>
<P>
The joint declaration was reported to outline a proposed series
of steps toward integration of the Turkish occupied northern
island.
</P>
<P>
It states that the partial integration in economic and
financial areas and partnerships in the fields of security,
defense and foreign policy, will coincide with Cyprus' European
Union (EU) membership.
</P>
<P>
The EU has confirmed to start the accession talks with Cyprus
next year, a move which was rejected by Turkey and the Turkish
Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, who was Turkey's Prime Minister in 1974, attended
celebrations organized Sunday in the northern part of Cyprus to
mark the 23rd anniversary of the Turkish invasion of the island.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as claiming that the Turkish Cypriot regime in
the north "will live for ever as an independent state, but its
foreign policy and defense will be handled by Turkey."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally a breakaway state
"the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which was only
recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters whether the Greek Cypriot side might
reconsider its decision to take part in a second round of direct
talks, Clerides said "the issue will be discussed in depth both at
the meeting of the National Council, top advisory body to the
President on the Cyprus problem, on Thursday, and with the Greek
government."
</P>
<P>
The first round of direct negotiations between Clerides on the
Greek Cypriot side and Turkish Cypriot leader Ruaf Denktash, for a
solution to the protracted Cyprus problem, took place in
Troutbeck, near New York, on July 9-12 and a second round of talks
is scheduled for August 11-16, in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island was divided since 1974 when
Turkish troops landed and seized the northern third in the
wake of a Greek Cypriot coup engineered by military junta
ruling Greece at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
