<HEADLINE> Abducted Somali Aid Worker Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU,July 21 (Xinhua)-- The Somali aid worker working for
an American aid agency, abducted by unidentified gumen Friday
night, was freed today.
</P>
<P>
The aid worker, Saed Aden Mohamed (Firdhis) was released
following an intensive talks by the North Mogadishu authorities
and representatives from the abductors.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdurahman Ahmed Mohamed, a program officer for
CARE International here in Mogadishu, Fordhis was released
unconditionally by his captors and was brought to Mogadishu from
Elow village, 40 km North of the capital, where he has been kept
by his abductors since Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Firdhis, a Somali aid worker working for the American aid
agency, CARE International, said after his release that he has
been treated and fed well during his captivity.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the abductors, the gunmen have
asked for a ransom of US $ 5000 for the release of Firdhis.
However, no such money was paid, but an undisclosed sum of money
was given out to the abductors, added the sources.
</P>
<P>
Firdhis was abducted by six gunmen driving a Land Rover near
his house in North Mogadishu where security was deteriorating
since October last year after the Islamic Sharia courts were
disabled following the political dispute between Ali Mahdi
Mohamed and the strong religious leader, Sheikh Ali sheikh
Mohamud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
