<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Israeli Official to Visit US to Discuss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu is planning to dispatch Cabinet Secretary
Danny Naveh to Washington soon to discuss new ideas on reviving
the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
This may signal the start of a new round of intensive
diplomatic offensive launched by Netanyahu after he averted
early this month a coalition crisis triggered by the resignation
of former finance minister Dan Meridor.
</P>
<P>
Naveh is to discuss with U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis
Ross and other officials new ideas put forward by Netanyahu on
breaking the ice in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks that have
been deadlocked since Israel began in March building the Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At the center of the new proposals was the suggestion that the
talks be taken on to a "fast track" to the final-status
talks. This means skipping the Oslo process, which requires
Israel to complete the three-stage troop withdrawals from West
Bank before August next year.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu even proposed accelerating the final-status talks in
order to conclude them as fast as within six months. The
permanent talks will tackle the most difficult issues of final
borders, status of Jerusalem and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hebron agreement signed between the two sides in
January, the final-status talks should have begun since
March. But the peace process have been frozen by the start of the
Har Homa construction.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's new ideas were believed to be based on the
so-called "Allon-Plus Plan", which was first publicized early
June by his aides as Israel's guidelines in the final-status
talks.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was the enlarged version of the plan proposed
by former Israeli foreign minister Yigal Allon after the 1967
war, envisioned Israel's relinquishing of only 40 percent of the
West Bank in the final settlement, while retaining control over
major settlements, water resources and strategic borders and
roads for national security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Knesset (Parliament) today, Netanyahu stressed
that all those ideas would only be implemented after the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) changes its approach toward
security, namely the handling of the alleged Palestinian police
involvement in anti-Israeli terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops arrested three Palestinian policemen last week,
who were allegely to be on their way to carry out a shooting
attack against a Jewish settlement near the West Bank city of
Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the Palestinian police of organizing riots and
terrorism, the Israeli government is pressuring the PNA to arrest
Ghazi Jabali, the commander of Palestinian police forces, who
was charged for masterminding the planned attack.
</P>
<P>
"We want a systematic action, an uprooting (of terrorism),
and steps be taken against those senior Palestinian officers
that were involved," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Palestinian police's uncovering of a bomb-making
factory run by the militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas)
near Bethlehem, Netanyahu emphasized that the Palestinian side
should launch a long-term crackdown on terrorism rather than
only take actions under Israeli pressure.
</P>
<P>
It remained doubtful if Netanyahu's new ideas could break the
ice in the peace process. The PNA wants to gain control over 80
percent of the West Bank in the final settlement, nearly double
the size in the "Allon-Plus Plan."
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his talks with Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy Sunday, PNA Planning Minister Nabil Shaath said the PNA was
not opposed to the idea of accelerating the final-status talks,
but required Israel to make concessions first by stopping
settlement activities and refraining from taking further
unilateral actions to derail the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition Parties Split up Following </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's opposition now seems
deeply divided as some opposition leaders called today for
boycotting talks with President Daniel arap Moi, while some
others are to attend the talks expected tomorrow or the day
after.
</P>
<P>
At the core of the mounting schism within the opposition ranks
is believedly their discomfort at both Moi's tendency to choose
who to meet and who they can approve of as their representatives
at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Only after Moi "unequivocally" affirms acceptance of the
constitutional reforms before the forthcoming general
elections, the talks can be held, Kivutha Kibwana, chief of the
National Convention Executive Council (NCEC), urged at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
So far "there have been no wide consultations to ensure that
there is genuine, open and democratic dialogue," leaving the
expected talks nothing meaningful, said Kibwana.
</P>
<P>
NCEC, the umbrella body set up in April to coordinate the
opposition's campaign for constitutional reform, "has not been
invited" to take part in the talks, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he charged that the talks is Moi's cosmetic and public
relations exercise which " would only make the government " succeed
in emasculating the determination and will " of the opposition
which has advocated reforms for months.
</P>
<P>
"Piece-meal negotiations are unacceptable" and all talks
between Moi and the opposition on the issue should be held under
the auspices of the NCEC and within the institutional framework
the NCEC provides, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He announced the opposition will continue to hold rallies for
constitutional reform without seeking permits from the
authorities, including an already planned one in Mombasa
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the NCEC boycotting, the expected talks between Moi
and some prominent opposition leaders are surely to take place,
some local political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
However, it is yet to be known who have been chosen by Moi
from the opposition camp to participate in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 73, and in power for 19 years, in a sudden softening of
his hard stance, met opposition leader Kijana Wamalwa as well as
19 key religious leaders respectively last week.
</P>
<P>
The government now is drafting bills which will be presented in
two weeks to the current session of the parliament for enactment
of a commission to review the constitution and make proposals
for the repeal or amendment of laws charged as oppressive.
</P>
<P>
These laws include the Public Order Act on public rallies, the
Preservation of Public Security Act which allows detention
without trial, as well as other nine laws.
</P>
<P>
The government's shifts came days after the most violent
conflicts between the police and the opposition supporters, which
claimed 13 lives around the eastern African country on July 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
