<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Sets to Compensate War Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today announced that a commission of inquiry will look into the
disbursement of war victims' compensation, which is looming into
sticky problem to the government.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member commission of lawyers and doctors is chaired by
Justice Godfrey Chidyausiku.
</P>
<P>
''You will be required to give measures of recovering all such
amounts of compensation as may have been improperly paid in
contravention or in excess of the qualifications and requirements
prescribed in the compensation act,'' Mugabe told the commission.
</P>
<P>
The government suspended payments under the act in March this year
following discoveries and allegations that undeserving people had
benefited from the fund.
</P>
<P>
War veterans, irked by the suspension, have taken to the streets
demanding the immediate release of the money.
</P>
<P>
Today, about 1,500 ex-combatants, mostly soldiers who had
taken part in the long struggle for national liberation in the
70s, staged a demonstration in Harare demanding an audience with
Mugabe over the disbursement of the war victims compensation
fund.
</P>
<P>
Chanting slogans and denouncing some government officials, they
sang revolutionary songs outside the gate of the president office.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe used to be a British colony, called Southern
Rhodesia, at the end of 19th century. Zimbabwean people carried
out decades of struggle against British colonialists and won its
independence on April 18, 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
