<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Genocide Suspects Arrested in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) said today that seven genocide
suspects arrested in the Kenyan Capital last Friday were using
false passports, mostly from the Francophone countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Arusha, northern Tanzania,
Deputy Prosecutor Bernard Muna said that documents found with
them were false and "We're scrutinizing the documents".
</P>
<P>
He denied reports from Nairobi that ICTR had arrested another
additional 80 Hutu genocide suspects, pointing out that the
tribunal has nothing to do with the weekend's arrests in Nairobi
by the Kenyan police. "Maybe it was a normal clean up exercise of
the Kenyan police," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed any suggestion that there was link between
Friday's arrests and a visit Wednesday by Rwanda's Vice-President
Paul Kagame.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR would prepare an indictment within maximum 90 days
for those suspects arrested in Nairobi, he said.
</P>
<P>
President of the tribunal, Judge Laity Kama, who also attended
the press conference, praised the co-operation of the Kenyan
government in arresting the suspects and urged other African
countries to offer help to bring to justice the leading
architects of the Rwandese genocide in which an estimated number
of over 500,000 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
He said that some African countries, he said without
mentioning names, have been issued with arrest warrants of
suspects, "but there are no good co-operation and this delays the
work of the tribunal."
</P>
<P>
On the allegations of Rwandan people that the tribunal is slow
in prosecuting those who committed genocide, the ICTR president
assured that everything possible was being done and promised that
cases would be speeded up after second trial courtroom will be
ready next month.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Jean Kambanda, Rwanda's interim Prime
Minister during the 1994 genocide, was among those arrested
during a series of dawn raids in Nairobi on Friday. The other
arrested were also dignitaries in the former Rwandan regime who
occupied positions of political or military responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The arrested were immediately transferred to the detention
facility of the tribunal in Arusha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
