<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, India Inaugurate Joint Venture of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and India inaugurated today a
phosphoric acid plant worth 170 million U.S. dollars in southern
Jordan to guarantee sustainable supply of the product to the
Indian market.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan who attended the occasion said at
the inauguration ceremony that the setting up of the plant was the
progression of the national economy and will bring the South
Asian market closer to Jordan, according to Radio Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is expected to produce about 250,000 tonnes
of phosphoric acid annually.
</P>
<P>
All the products will be exported to India, where they will be
used to manufacture diammonium phosphate, a fertilizer greatly
demanded by Indian farmers.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is Jordan's first major project set up under
its strategy to promote the export of finished fertilizers instead
of rock phosphates.
</P>
<P>
The plant is a joint venture between India's Southern
Petrochemical Industries Corporation Limited (SPIC) and the
Jordanian Phosphate Mines Company (JPMC).
</P>
<P>
The JPMC raised 100 million U.S. dollars in international loans
and 6 million dollars from local banks to build the plant, which
is located in southern Jordan adjoining the largest rock-phosphate
mining facility in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture includes a branch plant producing 700
tonnes of phosphoric acid per day and a factory with a daily
output of 200 tonnes of sulphuric acid, in addition to associated
utilities at Shidiyeh and an acid storage facility at the port
of Aqaba, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been the world's fifth largest producer and third
largest exporter of rock phosphate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Welcomes European Role in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today voiced welcome to the recent European efforts to
break the impasse in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters here that he also welcomed the
discussions the European Union (EU) foreign ministers will have in
Brussels, Belgium Tuesday with the Palestinian and Israeli
sides in an attempt to review the situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Top Palestinian National Authority (PNA) negotiator Nabil
Shaath and Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy will meet at the
15-member EU's General Affairs Council meeting, as part of a
European bid to advance stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace moves.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat has yet to decide whether or not
to meet Levy there. But European officials said earlier they hope
the two sides could agree on confidence-building measures, mainly
to provide aid to the ailing Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Moratinos, EU's Mideast peace envoy, who arranged a
meeting between Shaath and Levy Sunday, said progress was made on
security issues.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Egypt, while following up the U.S. efforts,
continues to work for a balanced peace that satisfies the
legitimate demands of the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
"The important thing is to disentangle the peace process from
its current crisis and give it momentum in line with the terms of
reference of the Madrid peace conference," he said.
</P>
<P>
The top Egyptian diplomat added that all the U.S., European
and Arab peace initiatives are equally vital.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has stepped in as a major broker between the
Palestinians and Israelis since the U.S. lowered its mediation
profile in the four-month-old peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
A tripartite Arab meeting grouping Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, Jordan's King Hussein and Arafat is expected to take
place here before the end of this month, according to local
media reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
