<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Proposes to Extend Mandate of UNOMIG in Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today proposed to extend the mandate of the United Nations
Observer Mission in Georgia (UNOMIG) for a period of six months
until January 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Annan said that the Government of Georgia and
the Abkahaz authorities had reaffirmed their commitment to
resolving the conflict by political means and expressed support
for a more active role for the United Nations in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said that the key issues of the Georgian
peace process, such as the future political status of Abkhazia and
the return of refugees and internally displaced persons, remained
unsolved.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the Gali restricted weapons zone and in
particular, the security zone, had remained intense. Acts of
violence, including common crimes, continued to be a serious
problem. Most of the mine-related incidents were directed at the
CIS peacekeeping force, Abkahaz militia and the administration,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
In the light of progress in the political process and the
positive effects that UNOMIG continued to have in the situation,
Annan recommended that the Security Council extend the mandate
of UNOMIG in Georgia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
