<HEADLINE> Lesotho to Ask for World Poverty Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government will ask
for 775 million Rand (about 172 million US Dollar) from the
international donor community to implement a program to fight
poverty in the next five years, a senior Lesotho official said today.
</P>
<P>
Finance and Economic Planning Minister Leketekete Ketso made
the statement on the first day of a two-day round-table
conference on poverty reduction, held in the kingdom's capital
Maseru, reported the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
The conference was attended by about 200 representatives from the
public and private sectors as well as the donor communities.
</P>
<P>
Ketso said half of the Lesotho people were regarded as poor,
especially in the rural areas where 80 percent of the Basotho people
live.
</P>
<P>
He said main areas which needed attention include good governing,
improvement of social services, creation of new employment and income
opportunities, expansion of social funds and the management of
poverty-related environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho is a small land-locked country surrounded by South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
