<HEADLINE> African Health Conference Opens In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The biannual Social Science and
Health International Conference started here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 delegates from seven African countries are
attending the five-day conference with a theme of ''African
Health in the 21st Century''.
</P>
<P>
The conference seeks to bring together social scientists and
medical practitioners so they can find a holistic approach to health.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwe's Health and Child Welfare
Minister Timothy Stamps urged African governments to implement efficient
mechanisms for identifying and assisting people with hereditary,
genetic and environmental illnesses.
</P>
<P>
He said such illnesses were difficult to modify and militated
against attempts to achieve the goal of good health for most
populations.
</P>
<P>
''In managing and mitigating their deprived or deficient
circumstances clearly, this requires more than dishing out fancy
pills or satisfying the ubiquitous passion for an injection,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
Stamps also castigated the World Trade Organization for granting
private institutions patents to genes, including those of human
beings, which could be transferred to animals to produce additional
sources of organs like hearts and kidneys to be used in human
transplant operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
