<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Consider Nuclear Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian Minister of Nuclear Power
Engineering Viktor Mikhailov and visiting U.S. Secretary of Energy
Federico Pena discussed here on Monday the bilateral cooperation
in the field of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, the sides focused on
the implementation of the agreement on turning highly-enriched
uranium into a low-enriched one, and on the removal of
restrictions for the trade with the United States in uranium
products.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass quoted the Russian ministry's press service as
saying that both leaders also specified Russia's right to dispose
of the natural component of the nuclear fuel produced from uranium
which is extracted from the dismantled nuclear charges and sent to
the United States for its nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
Mikhailov and Pena agreed to continue joint activities in
creating new types of nuclear reactors on fast neutrons.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also exchanged views on the meeting of the
Russian-U.S. Chernomyrdin-Gore commission scheduled for September.
</P>
<P>
During today's meeting the two sides signed a joint statement
which says that "the research institute of instruments in
Lytkarino is now the part of the Russian-American cooperation on
counting, control and physical protection of nuclear materials."
</P>
</TEXT>
