<HEADLINE> S. African Businessmen Urged to Invest in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice President
Oomar Ali Juma today called upon the South African Business
community to invest in Tanzania saying the country has necessary
economic potentials yet to be exploited.
</P>
<P>
Opening the one-day trade seminar organized by the Ministry of
Industries and Trade in collaboration with South African High
Commission here, Juma told about 40 South African businessmen that
Tanzania had excellent business environment ranging from Natural
endowments to peace and national unity.
</P>
<P>
He said despite the natural endowments, the country's
geographical location was an asset to further transit trade with
landlocked neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said unlike many other countries,
Tanzania's problem was not lack of natural endowments, but rather
the means to tap the country's natural potential.
</P>
<P>
"Substantial financial resources combined with requisite human
skills and technology are required to exploit these potentials
into tangible projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
Juma said that among the foreign investors in the country,
South Africa had comparative advantage taking into account its
technology, geographical proximity and the emerging in depth
knowledge among business communities.
</P>
<P>
He urged the South African businessmen to establish economic
projects between the two countries in the spirit of South-South
Commission. 
</P>
