<HEADLINE> Arafat to Travel to Brussels Likely to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat decided today to attend an EU Council of Ministers
meeting in Brussels amid speculations that he will meet Israeli
Foreing Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
However, Arafa's information advisor Nabil Abu-Rodaineh
indicated that it is not clear whether the Palestinian leader
will hold talks with Levy there. Arafat and Levy were invited to
address the gathering.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is expected to call on the EU to step up its
involvement in the peace process to try to break the impasse in
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Britain and Austria last week, Arafat
urged European leaders to use economic pressure against Israel
in order to reactivate the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Brokered by EU peace envoy Miguel Moratinos, Levy and
Palestinian Minister of Planning and International cooperation
Nabil Shaath met in Jerusalem Sunday night. Moratinos said that
another step had been taken to get the peace process back on
track.
</P>
<P>
"I think that if President Arafat will be in Brussels there
will be a meeting (between Arafat and Levy)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Levy said Sunday that his primary objective in going to
Brussels is to attend the EU meeting, but would not object to a
meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
"If Arafat happens to be there or not is not for me to
determine," he said, "If he is there and wants to hold a
meeting, why not? I do not anticipate, am not asking, and do not
invite." 
</P>
