<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Present Mir Crew not to Repair Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The present crew of the Mir orbital
station will not make a space walk, and the repair work which is
to be carried out by the present crew, will be done by Pavel
Vinogradov and Anatoli Solovyev in August.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency cited a source at the Mission Control
Center as saying on Monday, the flight of French astronaut Leopold
Eyhartz, scheduled for August 5, is likely to be put off.
</P>
<P>
This operation is opposed, above all, by Yuri Semenov, chief of
the Energia corporation, the firm which is the real owner of the
Mir station.
</P>
<P>
Semenov claimed that "the present crew made their utmost,
therefore they should not be trusted a space walkout." The
station's repairs should be made by Solovyev and Vinogradov who
are now industriously preparing for the flight at the Cosmonauts'
Training Center.
</P>
<P>
In Semenov's opinion, this would be an optimum version.
Besides, he suggests that periods of cosmonauts' return to earth
should be cut to September 12, instead of planned October 2 when
Tsibliev and Lazutkin were supposed to make their landing.
</P>
<P>
Semenov claimed that the crew and Mission Control who
overloaded the Progress M-34 cargo ship, are to blame for what
happened at the station, mostly for the puncture of the module.
The ferry developed another dynamics due to overload, which was
not taken into account either by crew commander Tsibliev or
Mission Control specialists.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, the Gagarin Cosmonauts' Training Center
believes that Tsibliev is not to blame for the collision and that
the Mission Control Center should not pay to the Energia
corporation for the damage inflicted on the station, which Semenov
is striving for.
</P>
<P>
The American NASA agency now takes a wait-and-see attitude,
while the French space agency, it is said, agrees to delay the
flight of the French astronaut for some time in the future, and
will not demand 60 million U.S. dollars which are already paid to
the Russian Space Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
