<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman has abandoned plans to supply natural gas to
Dubai, one of the seven sheikdoms of the United Arab Emirates
because of its limited gas reserves, Oman's oil minister said in
a press release which is available here today.
</P>
<P>
Said bin Ahmed al Shanfari said his country had considered to
provide Dubai with natural gas through a pipeline.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to do so," he said," but our limited reserves
have blocked this project."
</P>
<P>
Oman has earmarked the bulk of its gas resources for
liquefied natural gas ventures which it hopes will sharply boost
its income when it starts exports in 2000. Its small gas wealth
has also prompted it to drop an ambitious plan to supply India
with natural gas through an underwater pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Oman's gas reserves were estimated at around 750 billion
cubic meters at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A shipment of Egyptian medicine worth 5 million pounds
(1.47 million U.S. dollars) has been sent to Iraq, within the
framework of the U.N. oil-for-food program, the Egyptian Gazette
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Egyptian Holding Co. for Pharmaceuticals Galal
Gharib said in an announcement Sunday that he would hold a
meeting with an Iraqi trade and economic delegation currently
visiting Egypt to discuss Iraq's request to buy Egyptian
medicines and medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Five thousand tonnes of Egyptian soap arrived in Iraq by
mid-July while 5,200 tons of Egyptian industrial detergents will
be expected in the Iraqi market in ten days.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has purchased 50 million dollars worth of food from Egypt
since the implementation of the U.N.-Iraqi deal.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Twenty to 40 percent of the shares of the Egyptian
Pharmaceutical Company will be offered for sale at the stock
market in September, the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Holding Company for Pharmaceuticals Galal
Gharib was quoted as saying the stake amounts to 700,000 to 1.4
million shares, 10 percent of which would be sold to the company's
workers.
</P>
<P>
There was a general direction to offer only 40 percent of the
shares of pharmaceutical companies for public subscription
because of the industry's social dimension in Egypt, he said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) boosted spending
to a record high in 1996 as the government increased allocations
for subsidies, an official report showed today.
</P>
<P>
The total expenditure reached 19.6 billion U.S. dollars last
year, a more than 15 percent rise compared with 17 billion
dollars in 1995, said the latest report issued by the UAE Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Most of the spending increase that year went to allocations
for subsidies and government transfers abroad, which jumped to
about 4.7 billion dollars from 2 billion dollars in the previous
year, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
New jobs and promotions boosted allocations for salaries to
civil servants from 3.2 billion dollars in 1995 to 3.4 billion
dollars in 1996, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
