<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Report on Clinton-Yeltsin Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The White House today denied a
report that said U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian President
Boris Yeltsin will meet in Moscow next March or April.
</P>
<P>
There has been no decision on the timing or venue of any 1998
summit meeting between Clinton and Yeltsin, said White House
spokesman Michael McCurry.
</P>
<P>
McCurry made the comments on a report by Russia's Itar-Tass
news agency that Yeltsin would host Clinton in Moscow at a summit
that would focus on energy.
</P>
<P>
But he added, "We have a summit with President Yeltsin every
year and look forward to having a summit with him at some time in
1998."
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Eight agreed in Denver to hold a ministerial
meeting on energy issues, which may be where the confusion stems
from, in Moscow in 1998, with the results to be discussed at the
next Summit of the Eight in Birmingham, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"I do anticipate that President Clinton and President Yeltsin
will meet in 1998, as you would expect them to meet, but we have
not set a place or a time for said meeting," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Separately, the president and President Yeltsin had a casual
discussion (in Denver) about a summit in 1998, but nothing has
been fixed," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin met last month on the sidelines of the
Denver G-7 summit. Their last formal summit meeting took place in
March in Helsinki, Finland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
