<HEADLINE> S.Africa's Mining Giant to Tap Tanzania's Nickel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's mining
giant,the Anglo American Corporation, today signed an agreement
with a Canadian company, Sutton Resources Limited, for the
acquisition of a majority stake in a nickel and cobalt project
in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, signed in Dodoma, Tanzania and the
South African corporation will undertake a program of additional
exploration drilling at the Kabanga nickel-cobalt project in
north-western Tanzania, reported the local press.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study of the project will be completed in four
years.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Robert Danchin, Chairman of
Anglo's new mining business division in Tanzania, said he was
optimistic that the program of exploration and drilling, expected
to be conducted over the next 18 months, would provide the
necessary basis for the establishment of a mine and treatment
facility at Kabanga.
</P>
<P>
"We are encouraged by the support given to the project by the
government of Tanzania and trust that masks the beginning of a
successful and mutually beneficial relationship," said Danchin.
</P>
<P>
Kabanga forms part of a belt of nickelferous mineralization
that stretches from the Ugandan border in the north to the shores
of Lake Tanganyika in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The total capital investment to establish a mine and
associated facilities at Kabanga is estimated at 135 million US
Dollar. Anglo hopes to bring the mine to production in the year
2001. 
</P>
