<HEADLINE> Turkey Seeks Closer Ties With EU, Minister Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
left here today for Brussels for a Western European Union (WEU)
meeting, with a mission to strengthen the fragile Turkey-EU ties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the Ankara Esenboga Airport before
departure, Cem indicated that at the meeting, Turkey will seek to
improve its ties with the EU through WEU, of which Turkey is an
associate member.
</P>
<P>
He said the WEU ministerial meeting would approve a declaration
which is expected to be added into the EU Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has actively participated in the preparation of the
draft declaration which "we consider as positive in respect of
strengthening our status in WEU," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cem said Turkey will benefit from the close WEU-EU cooperation
as some WEU sponsor nations, such as France and Germany, are also
leading EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Cem also said the current WEU policies towards its associate
members are conducive to developments for Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey suffered a heavy blow when the European Commission
published a recommendation report recently excluding Turkey from
the ranks of prospective EU membership candidates.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of Cyprus into the candidate nations angered
Ankara even more due to the bitter experiences between Turkey
and island state, which maintains close ties with Greece, a
long-standing rival of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News said that the foreign minister will
also lodge Turkey's complaints over the membership to EU
officials in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
He will also explain Turkey's policies towards relations with
Athens to EU Foreign Relations Commissioner Hans Van Den
Broek, also former Dutch Foreign Secretary.
</P>
<P>
Though repeatedly stressing its "important relations with
Turkey", EU was reluctant to accept Turkey as a full member
state due to its human rights record, stance on the Cyprus
issue as well as its weak economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
