<HEADLINE> Taylor's Suspected Assassin Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A business leader arrested seven weeks
ago for alleged assassination attempt at presidential candidate of
former warlord Charles Taylor has been set free.
</P>
<P>
Also released are some 32 persons arrested for attempting to commit
electoral malpractices during Saturday's landmark election in
war-ravaged Liberia, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The order for the release was given by Major-General Victor Malu,
commander of the west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG which
is responsible for providing conducive security environment for the
election.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Mapison Wion, Managing Director of the
Forestry Development Authority of Liberia, has confessed his
involvement in the plot.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Taylor has voluntarily pardoned Woin and all those
involved in the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, conditions for Wion's release are based on the
fact that he has undertaken to desist from acts capable of undermining
peace in the country and also demonstrated in practical terms his
desire to reconcile with Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's presidential and parliamentary elections ended peacefully
on Saturday and is expected to bring final peace after seven years of
bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results from the country's Independent Elections
Commission show Taylor has won nearly 66 percent of the votes counted
so far.
</P>
<P>
The 219,754 votes already counted are collected from 684 of the
1,900 polling centers nationwide, including the capital Monrovia of
its environs.
</P>
<P>
Considering these areas are not the stronghold of Taylor, many
observers believe the National Patriotic Party candidate is now only
one step toward the top seat of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Taylor's closest rival, Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf of the
Unity Party, has reportedly alleged that the Nigeria-led ECOMOG
interfereed with the vote, especially where voters did not understand
the election process.
</P>
<P>
Sirleaf has received 34,914 votes, or 15.887 percent of the total,
ranking second among all the 13 presidential candidates, who promised
before Saturday's election that they would accept whoever wins.
</P>
<P>
Poll counting is still proceeding under supervision of ECOMOG and
international observers. The final results are expected on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
