<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Money Supply Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany's M-3 money supply has
settled down within the central bank's target range for the first
time this year, bolstering expectations that the central bank is
unlikely to raise interest rates to curb inflation in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
The M-3 measure of money supply grew by 6.4 percent in June
compared with the fourth quarter of 1996, well below the 7 percent
growth registered in May.
</P>
<P>
For 1997 as a whole, the German central bank has set a 3.5 to
6.5 percent corridor for the growth in M-3, which counts money
circulation, sight deposits, fixed deposits under four years and
savings deposits, an important barometer for the bank to measure
inflation and to make decisions on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, known as the Bundesbank, said a decline in
lending activities of both corporate and private borrowers was the
chief factor in June's slowdown in money supply growth. Borrowing
by the public sector was also weaker than in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
