<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Reports 38 percent Drop in 2nd-Quarter Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- AT&AMP;T Corp., the largest
long-distance operator of the U.S., said today that its profit
dropped 38 percent in the second quarter, despite a lightly
increase in revenues.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the drop was affected partly by the cost of
expanding into local phone and other markets and slow revenues
from its core long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
The company said it earned 959 million U.S. dollars in the
quarter ended June 30. That was down from 1.54 billion U.S.
dollars, in the year-ago period, excluding results from AT&AMP;T's
underwater cable unit, which it has since sold.
</P>
<P>
Revenues rose 2.4 percent to 13.17 billion U.S. dollars from
12.87 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from AT&AMP;T's core long-distance business grew only 1.5
percent to 11.582 billion U.S. dollars, dragged down by
competition for customers with price breaks and other promotions.
The slow growth came despite a 9.7 percent increase in calling
volume.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, a federal appeals court threw out key parts of new
regulations aimed at opening the 100 billion U.S. dollar local
phone market to long-distance companies and other rivals. It
would provide some chances for the long-distance provider.
</P>
</TEXT>
