<HEADLINE> Canadian Fishermen End Blockade of U.S. Ferry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Canadian fishermen have cleared the
way for an Alaskan ferry to leave the Canadian port of Prince
Rupert in British Columbia (B.C.) province, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
About 200 fishing-boats began to withdraw Monday night from the
three-day blockade within an hour of meeting federal Fisheries
Minister David Anderson.
</P>
<P>
Bob Rezansoff, a spokesman for the fishermen, said that they
have proved their point.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen "have a sense of accomplishment, of bringing the
issue to the attention of the public all over," he was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Anderson promised that he will ask his government to shoulder
some of the liability from B.C. fishermen who blockaded the ferry
in the B.C. port, some 1,500 kilometers northwest of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
A committee will also be formed to investigate possible
compensation for some of the poor B.C. fishing communities that
the blockaders were trying to help, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, nearly 400 fishing boats surrounded the Alaskan
ferry, preventing it from leaving the port.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen said the action was a protest against heavy
interception of Canada-bound salmon by Alaskan boats and Ottawa's
limited response.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the U.S. State Department called for an immediate
end to the blockade. It also hinted at retaliation against Canada
over the blockade.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing salmon war between Canada and the United States
started after the failure of negotiations in June over revisions
to the Pacific Salmon Treaty of 1985, which set salmon catches for
both countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
