<HEADLINE> Russian Military Reform Meets Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The apparatus of the Russian
Defense Ministry and some top brass in the army rose in opposition
to the military reform plan drafted by Russian Defense Minister
Igor Sergeyev and approved by President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev admitted today in an interview with the Izvestia daily
that "the reform has enough opponents although it is hard to
personify them."
</P>
<P>
The defense minister made it clear that the main rebuff to
reforms came from the bureaucratic apparatus of the Defense
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"We must cut and replace the apparatus of the Defense
Ministry ... It does not meet the demands of the present day,"
Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
He noted there were fervent opponents of the reform program
among high-ranking officers as well.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Kremlin unveiled a plan for military reform,
which aimed to turn the conscript-based forces into a leaner
professional war machine.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Russian troops will be cut by 500,000 to 1.2
million by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that after a meeting with Sergeyev on Monday,
President Yeltsin declared that the number of generals in Russia
will be cut down to 2,300, which means more than 500 top brass
will be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
The minister is convinced that a military reform shall be
launched immediately. But he did not rule out the possibility of a
collapse of the reform.
</P>
<P>
"I am fully determined to take advantage of this moment. In
order to preserve the Russian Armed Forces, it is necessary to
begin an immediate and deep reform... If I fail, I shall have to
go," Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the success of reforms will depend on the support
of the army, especially the middle-ranking army servicemen.
</P>
</TEXT>
