<P>
LONDON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair today
invited the Liberal Democrats to join a cabinet committee, giving
a chance for Britain's third party to influence the Labor
government's policy.
</P>
<P>
Less than three months after coming to power with a massive
179-seat majority in parliament, Blair reached an agreement with
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown on a new consultative
committee that will look initially into constitutional reform.
</P>
<P>
An aide to Blair said that the cooperation was not the first
step towards a coalition government and that there was no
intention of appointing Liberal Democrats as ministers.
</P>
<P>
Establishing the committee of six senior ministers and five
Liberals, which will probably meet once a month, marked the prime
minister's desire to create a new politics in Britain by reaching
out to like-minded parties, he added.
</P>
<P>
"This is the real beginning for a different style of politics
in Britain," Ashdown told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition Conservatives said the agreement deprived
the Liberals of the right to be regarded as opponents of Blair.
</P>
<P>
Labor officials acknowledged that one of the aims of the
committee was to bind the Liberal Democrats closer to Labor in
case the ruling party ever needed their parliamentary support.
</P>
<P>
Top of the agenda for the committee will be issues such as the
devolution of power to Scotland, Wales and English regions, the
possible introduction of proportional representation for the House
of Commons, and reform of the House of Lords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
