<HEADLINE> Oman to Open Office in Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Oman decided today to open a
representation office in Gaza to show its support for the Middle
East peace process, the Omani news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Oman's Foreign Ministry said in a statement issued today that
the opening of the office is aimed at backing the Middle East
peace process which has been stalled since March due to Israel's
hardline settlement policies. It gave no further details of the
decision.
</P>
<P>
Oman has repeatedly urged Israel to stop the construction of
thousands of houses in East Jerusalem which Palestinians want to
be their capital of a future state.
</P>
<P>
Oman is the second Arab Gulf state to open an office in Gaza
after Qatar. Egypt, Jordan, Morocco and Tunisia also have
representatives in Gaza, the seat of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Ambassador Salem Bin Fankhar al-
Shanfari has been appointed to head the office in Gaza, but no
date has been set for its opening.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the case with most Arab states, the PNA has no
diplomatic representation in Muscat, capital of Oman.
</P>
</TEXT>
