<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth African African-American Summit Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A four-day fourth African
African-American summit started here today with a series of
workshops expected to contribute to policy formulation, economic
development and social activities that will help improve the
quality of life of Africans.
</P>
<P>
The workshops will discuss issues ranging from agriculture,
arts and culture, business and economic development,
communications and the media, education, health, peace, democracy
and governance, population and women's issues.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe is expected to officially
open the conference on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said more than 1,000 delegates including
at least 20 African heads of state and government confirmed their
participation at the summit. Most African leaders are expected
to arrive in Harare on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A number of American experts and businesspersons also attended
the summit set to encourage investment and aid to Africa.
</P>
<P>
Today, the communications and the media workshop examined the
impact of information on relations between Africa and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, chairman of the Inner City Broadcasting of
New York Pierre Sutton noted that the exchange of information
between Africa and the rest of the world was cumbersome,
expensive, often one-sided and generally not considered to be
newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian journalist Uche Ezechukwu commented that the impact
of the foreign press on Africa was quite pervasive.
</P>
<P>
He said African Americans should let their "brothers and
sisters" on the African continent give them positive views about
Africa and not through foreign-owned media.
</P>
<P>
The communications and media workshop aims to help create
viable African media outlets so that information between Africa
and the rest of the world could be transferred efficiently and
effectively.
</P>
<P>
At a workshop on women, the delegates called on African
governments to provide special guarantees for women as collateral
security when they borrow money for business projects from banks.
They also urged women entrepreneurs to improve their ability to
access credit through training.
</P>
<P>
The delegates hoped the summit would not be another talk shop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
