<HEADLINE> Kasparov Says Playing Karpov Not Worth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Garry Kasparov, unofficial world
chess champion, said Tuesday that his match with Anatoly Karpov,
the World Chess Federation (FIDE) champion, may never take place
because Karpov's weak playing.
</P>
<P>
Kasparov was quoted as saying that "People who initially wanted
to give money for the match concluded that our duel would have no
sports intrigue. They think that the final result is slightly
predictable."
</P>
<P>
Kasparov became world champion in 1985 aged just 22, beating
his compatriot Karpov who had been the undisputed king of chess
for the previous 10 years.
</P>
<P>
But Karpov regained the title when FIDE sanctioned Kasparov for
setting up the breakaway Professional Chess Association in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Karpov-Kasparov match was designed to end their bitter
rivalry on the eve of the newly-designed world championships, due
to start in December with prize money totalling five million
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
