<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Expects Cyprus' Rival Community Leaders to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash are expected to meet very
soon here to discuss humanitarian issues, a U.N. official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Clerides,
U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel said the
U.N. expects that "the meeting between Clerides and Denktash will
go on."
</P>
<P>
He noted the two leaders are likely to meet "very soon" at his
residence here -- anytime before August 11, when the second round
of U.N.-led direct talks are scheduled to convene near Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The first round of direct talks between the leaders of the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities took place at Troutbeck near
New York on July 9-12. During the talks, the two leaders decided
to have a meeting in Nicosia, under the U.N. auspices, to discuss
humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether issues such as confidence building measures may
be discussed during the Nicosia meeting, Feissel said "it is for
them to decide what they want, but the focus is on humanitarian
matters."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official refrained from any comment on a joint
declaration issued Sunday by Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit and Denktash threatening the "partial integration" of the
Turkish-occupied Northern Cyprus into Turkey, if the island joins
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, which was rejected by the Greek Cypriot
side, outlines a series of steps toward partial economic and
financial integration, and partnership in the fields of security,
defense and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he was worried that Denktash may refuse to attend the
second round of talks in Switzerland, Feissel said "as we had
announced in Troutbeck, the meeting arrangements remain to be
confirmed, but we look forward to having the meeting."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the
island nation as a bi-communal, bi-zonal federation through peace
talks, but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Port of Entry Opens on China-Kirghizstan Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The second port of entry following
Turugart on the border of China and Kirghizstan opened Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new crossing point, in Wuqia County in the southwestern
part of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, is an
international port of entry, open to any country. It will provide
service in the last 10 days of every month till the end of July
next year.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the endeavor to cater to China's booming trade
with Kirghizstan and Uzbekistan. Statistics show that the trade
volume between China and Kirghizstan reached 136 million US
dollars-worth in 1996, and the figure for China-Uzbekistan trade,
170 million US dollars-worth.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Xinjiang has set up more than 40 solely- or
jointly-funded enterprises in Kirghizstan, involving a total
investment of over four million US dollars, and has opened four
international transport routes.
</P>
<P>
The port of entry is also on a section of the ancient "Silk
Road". Authorities say that it will help revive the famous trade
route.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
