<HEADLINE> Iraq Presents New Distribution Plan to U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has presented to the
U.N. Security Council a new plan for the distribution of the
humanitarian goods to be bought under the renewed "oil-for-food"
deal.
</P>
<P>
Nazar Hamdoun, Iraqi ambassador to the U.N., submitted the plan
Monday, which had been agreed upon by the U.N. program coordinator
in Baghdad, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
But the INA report gave no details about the distribution
proposal.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with the rotating president of the U.N. Security
Council for this month,
</P>
<P>
The INA report quoted Hamdoun as saying that only after the
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan ratifies the new plan, can his
country resume exporting oil.
</P>
<P>
At the end of May, Iraq fulfilled its quota of oil export in
the first six months' period under the "oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, the Security Council agreed to renew the
deal for another six months, under which Iraq is allowed to sell
oil to raise cash for the purchase of food and other daily
necessities badly needed in the sanctions-stricken country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under a harsh U.N.-imposed sanctions since
August, 1990 following its invasion of the oil-rich neighbor
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
