<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Fishermen Continue Blockade of U.S. Ferry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian fishermen continued to
hold the U.S. ferry Malaspina captive at Prince Rupert, British
Columbia (B.C.), for a third day today despite a court injunction
calling for its release.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Fisheries Minister, David Anderson, has reportedly
arrived in this coast community in a bid to free the U.S. ferry.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen, frustrated by the lack of action of the federal
government, took the action themselves to protest the U.S. state
of Alaska's overfishing of Canadian-bound sockeye.
</P>
<P>
Though the Alaskan government obtained an injunction from a
Canadian federal court on Sunday ordering the end of the blockade,
there has been little effect.
</P>
<P>
And more Canadian fishing boats and pleasure boats are reported
to have joined the siege today.
</P>
<P>
Tension began to rise in Prince Rupert on Friday after the
United States admitted it had caught more than three times its
limit of sockeye that spawn in Canadian waters.
</P>
<P>
That night, dozens of Canadian fishing boats surrounded two
U.S. salmon vessels to prevent them from delivering their
catch. And one U.S. boat collided with a Canadian vessel.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, some 200 boats surrounded the Alaskan ferry
carrying about 300 passengers, preventing it from leaving port.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen said they wanted Anderson to restart the salmon
talks with the U.S. and allow northern B.C. fishermen to increase
their take of sockeye.
</P>
<P>
They also wanted transit fees imposed on all U.S. marine
traffic along the B.C.'s northern coast.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing salmon war between Canada and the United States
started after the failure of negotiations over revisions to the
Pacific Salmon Treaty of 1985, which set salmon catches for both
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Host World Acupuncture-Moxibustion Conference (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Academic Conference of the
10th Anniversary of the World Federation of Acupuncture-
Moxibustion Societies (WFAS) is expected to be held here from
November 1 to 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the conference, which is sponsored by the WFAS and
the World Health Organization (WHO), and hosted by the Chinese
Acupuncture and Moxibustion Society, is "Acupuncture and
moxibustion in the new century," said Shen Zhixiang, director of
the Foreign Affairs Department of the State Administration of
Chinese Traditional Medicine and secretary-general of the
conference's preparatory committee.
</P>
<P>
Shen said the participants will review and summarize the
developments in the science of acupuncture and moxibustion in the
past decade, and discuss its new development trends in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 Chinese scholars and 500 experts from over 30
countries and regions have registered to attend the conference,
and some 700 papers have been received, he said.
</P>
<P>
The WFAS was founded in Beijing in November 1987. It held the
first academic conference the same year and another three
conferences of the same kind in France, Japan and the United States,
respectively, in the subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
The organization began to publish a magazine, named "World
Acupuncture and Moxibustion", in 1991. It has been distributed
worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
