<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Threatens to Impose Ban Over EU Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
threatened to ban beef imports from the rest of the European Union
(EU) if its EU partners refused to tighten their control on beef
processing.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with BBC Radio this morning, British
Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham said he would call on his EU
counterparts at a meeting in Brussels later today to adopt the
same stringent health standards as Britain in their abattoirs.
</P>
<P>
"I shall lay orders in the House of Commons to ensure beef
imported to Britain must be subject to the same treatment and the
same rigorous safeguards for public health as our own beef in this
country, or it will not be allowed into the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cunningham explained: "I'm on very strong grounds in European
policy terms and in safeguarding the health of the British people
to do exactly that, and that's what I will do."
</P>
<P>
The British Agriculture Minister noted Britain had raised
hygiene standards since the EU imposed a worldwide ban on British
beef exports in March 1996 after London admitted possible links
between the BSE, or mad cow disease, and its human equivalent
Creutzdfelt Jacob Disease.
</P>
<P>
The British government has repeatedly urged the rest of the EU
to emulate British abattoirs by removing and destroying the brain,
spinal cord, spleen and other parts of cattle most at risk of
carrying the BSE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
