<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Host World Acupuncture-Moxibustion Conference (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese people began to apply acupuncture in medical
treatment as early as 3,000 years ago, said Professor Deng
Liangyue, secretary-general of the WFAS.
</P>
<P>
Modern acupuncture skills include traditional needle
application and moxibustion techniques, as well as technological
methods such as electricity, magnetic influence, lasers,
ultra-violet rays and microwaves. These are all applied to
stimulate acupoints on the "meridians and collaterals" of the
human body, Deng explained.
</P>
<P>
Acupuncture can be used to treat more than 300 kinds of
diseases, those involving pain and functional disorders in
particular, he noted. It can also improve the immunity and
adaptability of the body.
</P>
<P>
Working in co-operation with the WHO, China set up three
international acupuncture training centers in 1975 -- in Beijing,
Shanghai and Nanjing, respectively -- which train acupuncture
practitioners for countries all over the world.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, the WHO published a list of 43 kinds of ailments which
can be treated with acupuncture and moxibustion.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are acupuncturists in more than 120 countries
and regions. Acupuncture research and education are also being
carried out in many countries, where it has become an important
part of medical treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
