<HEADLINE> Girl Dropouts Aided to Go to School in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Thirty girls from poverty-stricken
rural China will have a chance to attend school in Beijing with
the support of a US consumer goods manufacturer, as part of a
national help-girl-dropouts program.
</P>
<P>
Procter &AMP; Gamble has donated 170,000 yuan (about 20,500 US
dollars) to set up a "Spring Bud" junior middle school class, the
company's spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
The girls come from rural areas in 12 inland provinces such as
Shaanxi, Gansu, Ningxia, Qinghai, Yunnan and Guizhou, as well as
the suburbs of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The girls, all top graduates from "Spring Bud" primary schools,
will continue their studies at Beijing's Hepingli Secondary School.
</P>
<P>
The "Spring Bud Project", established in 1989 by the China
Children and Teenagers' Fund under the leadership of the All-China
Women's Federation, has helped some 430,000 girl dropouts
throughout China. Girl dropouts account for two thirds of all
dropouts in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
