<HEADLINE> Building HK on Education One of SAR's Priorities: Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) said today
that building Hong Kong on education is one of the priorities of
the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
"Education in Hong Kong should maintain its diversity and
incorporate the strength of the Chinese and Western cultures. It
should also improve students' understanding of Chinese culture and
history, thus encouraging them to care more for the future of our
country," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing ceremony of the week-long "Building
Hong Kong on Education" project here, Tung stressed the importance
 of drawing up a comprehensive plan and injecting sufficient
resources to improve the quality of education.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government would speed up the implementation of
full-day schooling to all primary schools and strengthen the
standard of language training and information technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government will also promote a balanced development on
"ethics, the intellect, the physique, social skills and
aesthetics", and enhance students' understanding of Hong Kong, the
 country and the world, he continued.
</P>
<P>
Tung also promised to raise the professional qualification of
teachers and updating tertiary education.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the young people of Hong Kong in the next century
would treasure traditional Chinese virtues and have a new mission
towards oneself, the family and the country. They should be able
to distinguish between right and wrong, care for the community and
keep up with the times.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, they need a wide range of knowledge, think
independently and have good communication skills, he said.
</P>
<P>
The "Building Hong Kong on Education" project featured an
exhibition, an international conference on "Language, Education
and Culture", a gala week and a series of school and community
building activities.
</P>
<P>
The project is jointly organized by the Home Affairs Department
and Lingnan College with the assistance of seven other University
Grants Committee-funded tertiary institutions to celebrate the
Hong Kong's return to China.  
