<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Glacial Lake Causes Panic in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Will it burst or not? That's the
question. It is simply because the Tsho-Rolpa glacial lake in the
Himalayas has not only caused panic in the flood-prone areas, but
also arrested the attention of the whole of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The drama unfolded when studies revealed in mid-June that the
glacial lake, situated 4,580-meter high in the Rolwaling Valley
about 80 kilometers east of here, has expanded from 1.37 sq.m. to
1.65 sq.m. and might burst this summer.
</P>
<P>
The studies further showed that the melting process of the
lake, detected in 1996, has sped up along its northwestern side,
and its water volume has reached 80 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Some experts warned that if the lake bursts, 40 million cubic
meters of water will gush out and affect 18 villages along the
Rolwaling River banks, including the Khimti Hydro-electricity
Project.
</P>
<P>
Being the most extensively studied glacial lake in the
Himalayas, the 3 kilometer-long and half a kilometer-wide
Tsho-Rolpa saw a minor burst of its neighboring Tshubing glacial
lake in July 1991.
</P>
<P>
That Tsho-Rolpa might also burst one day has been warned of
every now and then in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the renewed warning has caused panic immediately
among the locals who are in a constant state of trepidation.
</P>
<P>
They fear that water from such a burst would flood a wide area
and inflict serious damages, the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
As the monsoon season has set in, the fear has intensified.
</P>
<P>
The fear is so widespread that Tsho-Rolpa has become the
foremost topic in household conversations, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the disaster, some have moved to safer
regions while some just stay out of their houses at night.
</P>
<P>
Farmers who were compelled to harvest the maize crop before it
was ripe are just looking on helplessly with their fields
remaining barren and the cultivation season already past, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Aakashe Airport had to be closed for 20 days for fear of a
sudden outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Daily necessities become more expensive in the flood-prone
areas while incidents of theft and smuggling have also been on the
rise, it was reported.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has taken preventive steps to allay the
fear.
</P>
<P>
The Tsho-Rolpa Disaster Control and Management Committee under
the Home Ministry has been established, and a set of measures have
been taken including the evacuation of residents.
</P>
<P>
An alarm system is now in place and it can alert at-risk
communities within 5-7 minutes in the event of an outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, 10 police and army posts have been set up in
Dolakha and Ramechhap, the two districts expected to bear the
brunt of a burst.
</P>
<P>
If a burst happens, observers from an army base camp in Na, the
village immediately adjacent to the lake, will instantly alert
personnel at the Home Ministry via satellite phones. These
personnel will then send messages to the 10 police and army posts,
which will set off the sirens to alert the surrounding communities
to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the water volume of the lake, one complete siphon has
been installed. An older one set up earlier by a Dutch team has
been reactivated.
</P>
<P>
Together, the two siphons are capable of mitigating water from
the lake at a rate of about 420 liters per second. Once another
four are installed as planned, the rate will be up to 900 liters
per second, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to install a total of 32 siphons in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
While it is impossible to predict exactly whether and when the
lake may burst, some experts argued that the intensity of the risk
has been exaggerated by the media.
</P>
<P>
These experts said fears gripping government officials and
locals are turning out to be unfounded, because the lake has so
far shown no definitive signs of breaking this monsoon.
</P>
<P>
Even if it does, the burst will occur in stages rather than at
one go, and most of its fury will have dissipated before the
onrushing waters reach populated areas, they said.
</P>
<P>
Yet it is undisputable that the lake is a risk site for a
glacial lake outburst flood (GLOF), and natural disasters are
usually unpredictable not only in terms of the exact time of
occurrence but also in terms of the damage they could inflict.
These more than anything else call for preparedness, some experts
warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Urges Faster Development in Inner Mongolia (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua has spoken
highly of the economic achievements and historic changes which
have taken place in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region in the
past 50 years since its founding.
</P>
<P>
At an economic work forum to mark the founding anniversary of
the region, China's first autonomous ethnic-minority region, he
congratulated the people of various ethnic groups, the Party and
government officials, the PLA men and officers, and the armed
police in Inner Mongolia, on behalf of the Central Committee of
the Communist Party of China and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Zou particularly noted that the 18 years since the launching of
the reform and opening-up drive in 1978 had been the best period
for the region, which has recorded rapid economic development,
with the average annual economic growth rate hitting 9.7
percent. The region has quadrupled its GDP five years ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, Inner Mongolia is enjoying prosperous economic
development, which has laid a solid basis for achieving
social stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
By 1996 the grain output in Inner Mongolia had totaled 13
billion kg, successfully achieving self-sufficiency in grain
supply. Its animal husbandry sector has achieved bumper harvests
for 12 consecutive years, with the number of animals head topping
60 million head.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the region increased the number of its larger animals
by 7.349 million head and produced 921,000 tons of pork, beef and
mutton, representing increases of 110 percent and 440 percent
respectively over the figures for 1980.
</P>
<P>
The region, which had virtually no industry before 1949, is now
a leading production base for energy resources and raw materials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Urges Faster Development in Inner Mongolia (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The region had developed an annual coal production capacity of
80 million tons and electricity generating capacity of 32 billion
kwh by 1996.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1980, Inner Mongolia has increased its railway
mileage by an additional 1,400 km and highway mileage by 10,000
km. And its annual railway and highway passenger transport
volumes have more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the urban and rural telephone exchange capacity in
the region has been expanded from 130,000 to 1.3 million lines,
which has effectively enhanced the region's posts and
telecommunications capacity.
</P>
<P>
The target of the region's Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) and
the Development Program to the Year 2010 demands that the region
put into force five strategic measures involving the development
of resources, opening-up drive, science and education, skilled
personnel and famous-brand products. It urges that priority be
given to readjustment of the industrial structure, enhancement
of economic returns and tapping of markets.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier stressed that Inner Mongolia should strive to
develop the market-oriented economy. It must not only probe into
its own markets, but also markets in the surrounding areas,
and even the national and international markets.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia should give full play to its
own advantages and steadily expand them, he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged the region to pay close attention to the application
of scientific research findings to practical work. He said that
leading officials at all levels should constantly upgrade their
scientific and technological knowledge, and work out preferential
policies in support of the development and popularization of
advanced technologies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Zou asked the autonomous region to take the path of
sustainable economic development and protect its mineral, forest,
water and grass resources in an even better way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
