<HEADLINE> Suffocating Weather Afflicts Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijingers are suffering from hot
weather again after a heavy rainfall over the weekend, and they
complain that walking in the street is like "taking a sauna".
</P>
<P>
Afternoon data from the Beijing Meteorological Observatory
shows that the highest temperature in the urban area today again
exceeded 35 degrees centigrade, and the figure in Tiananmen Square
reached 37.
</P>
<P>
The relative humidity today reached 62 percent, much higher
than the average for this season, which is about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the hot and suffocating weather will see
little change in the coming few days. "The recent wet and hot
airflow from the south will make Beijingers feel like they are
living in the south," said Ding Deping, deputy director of the
Beijing Meteorological Observatory.
</P>
<P>
From July 8 to 15 Beijing experienced an eight-day heat wave,
with the highest daily temperature exceeding 35 degrees
centigrade; in some areas the figure even reached 39.5, rarely
seen in the past half a century.
</P>
<P>
Some local factories, shortly after returning to their normal
working hours, permitted their workers to go off duty two hours
early again today.
</P>
<P>
As power consumption by household air-conditioners is reaching
an unprecedented high, the Beijing Municipal Power Supply Bureau
has released a notice asking a number of dance halls to stop using
air-conditioners -- as a way to strike balance.
</P>
<P>
However, the bad weather is welcome to air-conditioner sellers,
for they are embracing a big boom of business. Purchasers have to
wait for about ten days for installation.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, some leading air-conditioner
manufacturers have stopped supplies to small shops in order to
cope with big department stores or shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
Some cities in northwestern China, including Xi'an and Lanzhou,
are also reporting a second heat wave. Today, the highest
temperature in Lanzhou reached 38 degrees centigrade. The city
used to be a summer resort for people running away from summer
heat elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
