<HEADLINE> Shanxi Moves to Self-Support in Grain Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Landlocked Shanxi Province in
north China has increased its grain production by 216 million kg
this summer, in a major step towards self-support in grain supply.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, there has been a sharp
contradiction between grain supply and demand in the province,
which used to buy an annual 700 million kg of grain from other
provinces. Its average annual per capita ownership of grain stands
at a mere 300 kg, lower than the national average.
</P>
<P>
To be self-sufficient in grain supply the province has launched
a massive campaign since 1996 to increase grain production.
</P>
<P>
It has earmarked special funds for the upgrading of farming
technologies and improvement of agricultural production
conditions, with priority given to nearly 30 counties, covering a
total area of 1.5 million ha, or 28 percent of the province's
total arable land.
</P>
<P>
Since the enforcement of a series of grain-boosting measures,
the province has improved nearly 11,000 ha of irrigated farmland
and popularized more than 10 up-to-date farming
technologies. Meanwhile, the mechanization of agriculture has been
greatly enhanced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New PNG PM Promises Inquiry Into Alleged Corrupt Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea's (PNG) new
Prime Minister Bill Skate today moved to rid his government of
corruption, promising to set up an inquiry to look at a number of
alleged corrupt deals involving the previous government.
</P>
<P>
Skate was elected prime minister today after defeating former
prime minister Sir Michael Somare by a vote of 71 to 35 in an open
ballot in the South Pacific nation's new 109-seat parliament, the
Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
"I've been a strong advocate of anti-corruption," the
44-year-old prime minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, he preempted it by saying many PNG leaders had been
brought undone by unsubstantiated allegations.
</P>
<P>
"There have been so many accusations, (but) there is no proof
and at the moment we have been accusing leaders and destroying
them," Skate told parliament.
</P>
<P>
Skate defeated Somare with the support of the country's four
major parties, including the previous ruling coalition of the
People's Progress Party (PPP) and Pangu Party.
</P>
<P>
Until the unlikely alliance was formed late Monday Somare and
Skate had the numbers to form a new government divorced from the
old regime.
</P>
<P>
Skate's tough stance against the 35 million US dollar contract
to use mercenaries to end Bougainville's separatist rebellion is
understood to have won his support from a block of independents in
his bid for the prime ministership.
</P>
<P>
Skate, who was an adviser to the former government of Paias
Wingti prior to winning the National Capital District seat of Port
Moresby in 1992, launched an unsuccessful no-confidence vote
against then prime minister Julius Chan in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
He formerly held a number of important public positions after
obtaining an accountancy degree from the University of Technology
in the city of Lae.
</P>
<P>
Australia, from which PNG gained independence in 1975, today
welcomed Papua New Guinea's new government.
</P>
<P>
Australian Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer said he wished
Skate well in meeting the many challenges the new leader faces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer announced
that he would visit PNG soon for talks with Skate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
