<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Bank's Renminbi Business Going Well in Pudong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Overseas bank branches here say
that their months-old Renminbi business is going well.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the central bank, has given
approval to nine branches of overseas banks in Shanghai to deal in
yuan-based business on a trial basis in the city's Pudong New
Area, an emerging trade and financial zone.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials say that six of the nine licensed overseas banks
have already started Renminbi business, including the Hongkong and
Shanghai Banking Corporation, the Mitsubishi Bank, the Industrial
Bank of Japan, the Sanwa Bank, the Daiichi Kangyo Bank, and
Citibank of the US.
</P>
<P>
However, some seven other overseas banks have set up branches
in Pudong in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the rules of the central bank, all overseas banks
hoping to do Renminbi business have to move their headquarters in
China to the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Bank and Citibank were the first to move to Pudong
in order to do Renminbi business last year.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Shanghai branch of the Mitsubishi Bank has opened
150 Renminbi accounts for local enterprises, according to bank
officials.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials say that the overseas banks are enhancing their
cooperation with local Chinese banks to increase their sources of
Renminbi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
