<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "China's Financial Situation Stable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- China has enjoyed a smooth financial
performance in the first half of this year, through keeping to a
moderately tight money policy, further adjusting the credit
structure and flexibly wielding financial instruments.
</P>
<P>
"Relatively good outcome was seen in controlling the macro
economy, furthering financial supervision, preventing financial
risks and thereby supporting economic growth," according to a
financial report by the People's Bank of China, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The money supply maintained a balance during the period. The
growth of broad money supply, at 19.1 percent, slowed by 6.2
percentage points compared to last year, indicating a further
lessening of inflationary pressure. The supply of narrow money, on
the other hand, saw a faster growth during the period, a sign that
the financial strain the enterprises have been suffering was eased
to some extent, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Cash in circulation, though maintaining relatively higher
growth than reasonable due to the overheated stock market and
bumper harvests last year, had little impact on the market and
reported normal circulation.
</P>
<P>
Deposits with the banks rose to 7.545 trillion yuan at the end
of June, up 19.8 percent over the beginning of this year. The
total amount broke down into 2.567 trillion yuan in enterprise
deposits and 4.277 trillion yuan in individual savings deposits,
up 27.5 percent and 19.7 percent during the period, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The rise in bank deposits has resulted in more credit funds for
economic development. The industrial sector received 79.8 billion
yuan more in loans, while the loans to the agricultural sector
increased by 44.71 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Renminbi yuan remained stable, while the foreign exchange
reserve continued to climb to 120.94 billion US dollars-worth, up
18.63 billion US dollars from last year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also called for further adjustment in the
credit mix to improve the economic structure, while stepping up
financial supervision to reduce and prevent financial risks, and
tightening control over cash to ensure effective recall of money
and a stable yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Disarmament Conference Opens in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A U.N.-sponsored disarmament
conference, aiming at seeking ways to end the current arms-cut
stalemate, today opened in the northern Japanese city of Sapporo,
said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference is expected to focus as much on control
of small arms and regional security issues as on its traditional
topic of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The agenda was a departure from the annual meeting's past
emphasis on nuclear testing and the prevention of the
proliferation of nuclear, chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Japanese State Foreign
Secretary Masahiko Komura, the No. 2 man in the Foreign Ministry,
said that there is a need to tackle conventional weapons,
including small arms, as part of the international disarmament
agenda.
</P>
<P>
"After all, it is conventional weapons that are actually
causing heavy casualties in regional conflicts and civil wars in
various parts of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
In particular, Komura urged controls on anti-personnel mines,
which he said "have killed and maimed many civilians, posing not
only a grave humanitarian concern, but also a large obstacle to
post-conflict efforts for reconstruction and development."
</P>
<P>
The conference, which has been held annually in Japan since
1989, is being attended by 79 diplomats, academics, government
officials and other experts from 32 countries.
</P>
<P>
While the first session still focused on nuclear disarmament,
three other sessions and working group meetings will tackle issues
including the prevention of the proliferation of small arms, roles
of regional security groups and maritime arms control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0104 </DOCNO>
