<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Japan Sign 3 Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Japan today signed
three agreements on a project for improvement of meteorological
radar network, construction of a mother and child health center
and debt relief grant.
</P>
<P>
A draft agreement on promotion and protection of investment was
also initialed here today when Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan held a meeting with his visiting Japanese counterpart
Yukihiko Ikeda.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides discussed matters of mutual
interest.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan briefed Yukihiko Ikeda on the recent political
development in Pakistan and also on the economic policies of the
government.
</P>
<P>
Yukihiko Ikeda said that Japan would continue its official
assistance to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government would also encourage the private sector
to increase economic cooperation with Pakistan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two foreign ministers also discussed matters
relating to the reform of the UN Security Council and the nuclear
non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
Yukihiko Ikeda arrived here on Monday night on a three-day
official visit. He is the first Japanese government official
visiting Pakistan since the present government led by Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif took over in February this year.  
</P>
