<HEADLINE> Arafat Raps US for Flagging Peace Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat today rapped the United States for its
diminishing input into the Mideast peace process and urged
unswerving aid to the Palestinian people, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"It was obvious that the U.S. administration has become more
occupied with other matters rather than the Mideast situation and
the peace accords...," Arafat told reporters after a meeting with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Egypt's Mediterranean city of
Alexandria this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader regretted that U.S. President Bill
Clinton has not done his part with a somewhat "unclear stand" in
the peace-making.
</P>
<P>
"In his capacity as one of the peace co-sponsors, (Clinton)
personally witnessed the signing of the peace accords which became
international. Hence, there is an American morale and political
responsibility regarding such agreements," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been blasted for its increasingly negative
attitude to the peace march and conniving in Israel's settlement
policy. In addition, a recent U.S. Congress resolution that
allocates funds to move the U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv
to Jerusalem also drew strong opposition from the international
community and Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he knew nothing of any Israeli initiative to
promote the peace march, brushing aside the so-called "bridging
ideas" Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Monday
Tel Aviv is working on jointly with Washington.
</P>
<P>
Arafat referred to the sufferings of the Palestinian people in
the West Bank cities of Hebron, Bethlehem, Rafah, Nablus and
Khan Yunis due to Israel's hardline measures.
</P>
<P>
"Conditions are now worsening than any other time," he said.
Israel has imposed embargoes upon the cities under Palestinian
control to prevent the spread of escalating violence into Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Peace, however, is not in the interests of the Palestinians
only, but it is in the interests of Israel, the U.S., and Russia
as well," he said before leaving for Brussels, Belgium, to attend
a meeting of foreign ministers of the European Union (EU) and
hold talks with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the reported French initiative to push the peace
march forward, Arafat said he is unware of such an initiative,
but there are European attempts supplementary to the Egyptian
ones to salvage the peace drive.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians welcome the European role in spite of the
Israeli rejection of any European endeavors so far," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the EU have stepped in as the major mediators
between the PNA and Israel as the U.S. efforts slacked off in the
the past four months.
</P>
<P>
Regarding his talks with Mubarak, the PNA president said they
evaluated efforts exerted and meetings held recently to
revitalize the peace process paralyzed in March by Israel's
building of thousands of Jewish homes in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mubarak meeting, following up Egyptian efforts to
push forward the Mideast peace process, was "more than positive
and important," he said.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting will be followed up by an enlarged
Egyptian-Palestinian meeting in Cairo Sunday to evaluate the
present situation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to host a tripartite summit among Mubarak,
Arafat and Jordan's King Hussein before the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace march has been deadlocked for
four months, with violence raging in both the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, however, refused to
give a temporary halt to the settlement expansion, a prerequisite
the Palestinians insist on for the resumption of
Israeli-Palestinian talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
