<HEADLINE> East, North Europe Potential Partners: Chemical Industry Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Enormous cooperative potential
exists in the chemical industry between China and the eastern and
northern European countries, according to Minister Gu Xiulian.
</P>
<P>
Gu Xiulian, minister of the Chemical Industry, made the remark
in an interview with Xinhua, just prior to her visit to Russia,
Poland and Finland.
</P>
<P>
Gu said that her visit will play an important role in
opening China's chemical industry wider to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
She added that she will introduce the developments scored by
China's chemical industry and the goals of China's Ninth Five-Year
Plan to those countries, and help promote mutual exchanges and
economic, trade, and technological cooperation with them in the
chemical industry, so as to spur the export of China's chemical
industrial technology and products.
</P>
<P>
"The three countries I will visit have their own advantages in
the chemical industry and have been cooperating with China for
years and have forged good cooperation relations with China," she
said, adding that there are bright prospects for cooperation
between China and the three countries.
</P>
<P>
She said that the chemical and petrochemical industries of
Russia have a solid foundation, as Russia leads the world in the
production of methanol, synthetic ammonia and chemical fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
China has already carried out cooperation in some chemical
industrial projects with Russia in Yunnan Province, Gu said. She
noted that the two sides will discuss problems cropping up in the
course of undertaking the cooperation projects during her visit to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides will discuss the introduction of technology,
equipment and funds during my visits to Poland and Finland," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The total trade volume of China's chemical industry reached
31.7 billion US dollars in 1996, with exports amounting to 12.4
billion US dollars and imports, 19.3 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that China will expand large-scale and in-depth
technological, economic and trade cooperation with the countries
she is about to visit, in line with the principle of mutual
benefit and common development.
</P>
<P>
She said she is convinced that China's cooperation with eastern
and northern European countries in the chemical industry will
enter into a new phase through better mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
She will make a 17-day tour of the three countries from July 23
at the invitation of the Russian Ministry of the Economy, the
Polish Ministry of the Economy and the Ministry of Trade and
Industry of Finland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
