<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Leader Condemns Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- South Mogadishu faction leader
today condemned the ongoing Ethiopian intervention in some parts
of Somali's southwestern region of Gedo.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of Prophet Mohamed's birthday, Hussein Aidid
called on Ethiopia to peacefully pull out its forces from Somali
soil before Somalis take up aggressive measures in defending
their country.
</P>
<P>
"Ethiopia should not start problems they will not be able to
find solutions for", he said.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid blamed Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi for
perpetrating the intervention into Somalia by his forces.
</P>
<P>
The Somalis can no longer tolerate the continuing provocation
of Ethiopia, he said, adding "I would like to remind Meles Zenawi
of the history and that the Somalis have the muscle to defend
their prestige and territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
"Let them look before they leap," said the 34-year-old
president of the self-proclaimed government established by late
warlord, general Aidid.
</P>
<P>
In another strong tone against the Ethiopian involvement in
Somalia, Hussein Aidid has castigated the recent meeting by the
Sodare factions and characterized the Ethiopian-sponsored
conference for 27 Somali factions as a sign of dividing the
country's unity.
</P>
<P>
The president called all Somalis including the religious
groups to be ready for defending their country.
</P>
<P>
On his recent meeting in Cairo with Ali Mahdi Mohamed, Hussein
Aidid said they discussed about the general reconciliation
efforts in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"We never spoke about anything related to Sodare or my future
participation in it," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
