<HEADLINE> Inland Publishing Houses Active at Hong Kong Book Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 7,000 kinds of books
rolled out by the Chinese inland publishing houses will be
exhibited at the upcoming Eighth Hong Kong Book Fair, scheduled
for July 23 to 28.
</P>
<P>
"To be held in Hong Kong less than one month after the historic
handover, this important get-together of the publishing community
is of great significance," said Yang Deyan, who headed a
155-member inland delegation for the six-day event.
</P>
<P>
Yang, director general of the 100-year-old Commercial Press,
told a news briefing here today that nearly 200 inland publishing
houses would bring to the fair about 20,000 copies of books,
ranging from social and natural science to literature, arts,
culture and education.
</P>
<P>
Out of 7,000-odd kinds of books, 89 have been picked up as
creme de la creme and will be displayed in a pool, including "Deng
Xiaoping: the Great Man of the Century", "Modern Chinese
Dictionary" and "A Comprehensive Collection of Lu Xun".
</P>
<P>
Wu Jiangjiang, president of the China National Publishing
Industry Trading Corporation, expected that the cooperation
between Hong Kong and inland publishing houses would be
strengthened after the handover. "As you will see, they will join
hands to promote books at this year's fair," he said.
</P>
<P>
At least 20,000 books are introduced to Hong Kong from the
inland areas each year, according to Wu, whose company is engaged
in foreign trade of books in China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
According to a Chinese official with the Press and Publication
Administration, there are over 500 publishing houses in the
Chinese inland areas, which in 1996 alone published more than
112,800 kinds of books, roughly 300 kinds of books a day. Books
printed in the year reached 7.158 billion copies, breaking the
hurdle of seven billion for the first time in the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council, the book
fair is the biggest of its kind in Asia. This year it is likely to
attract about 400 exhibitors, who will display their books in more
than 800 booths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
