<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong PLC Operates Successfully, Paper Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) has been operating successfully since its inception last
December, the Ta Kung Pao newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
It noted in a commentary that the legislature has made
remarkable achievements during the seven-month period by blocking
or passing a number of bills.
</P>
<P>
Before the handover, the PLC examined and approved 13 bills
indispensable to the HKSAR in the beginning of its establishment,
and adopted three other important motions, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
At its first meeting after the establishment of the HKSAR in
the small hours of July 1, the PLC passed the Reunification Bill,
confirming the 13 bills which had been passed by the legislature
prior to July 1 and dealing with various transition-related
matters.
</P>
<P>
The Reunification Bill also endorsed the appointment of the
justices of the Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the
High Court, Ta Kung Pao said.
</P>
<P>
On July 9, the provisional legislature pushed through an
immigration bill, or the Immigration (Amendment) No.5 Bill, in all
three readings. Under the bill, a certificate of entitlement
scheme is introduced for children born to Hong Kong permanent
residents in China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
These children are entitled to the right of abode in Hong Kong,
according to the Basic Law, but they must come in a legal and
orderly way.
</P>
<P>
The 60-member PLC endorsed a motion from the HKSAR government
on July 16 to suspend the operation of three labor-related
ordinances adopted by the pre-handover Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
After more than seven hours of lengthy debate, most legislators
were convinced that these laws had been adopted without careful
study of their impact and would harm the long-term interests of
Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
The previous Legislative Council rushed through these
ordinances proposed by radical unionists without making
consultations in its last legislative sitting four days before the
handover, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The daily stressed that the PLC has been playing a good role
since its establishment.
</P>
<P>
To avoid a legal vacuum immediately after the handover, the PLC
was elected in the southern China city of Shenzhen on December 21,
1996 by a 400-member Selection Committee, which was also
responsible for the selection of the first Chief Executive of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The provisional legislature will stop functioning when the
first Legislative Council of the HKSAR is established, not later
than June 30, 1998, under a decision made by the Preparatory
Committee for the HKSAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
