<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Fighting Rebels Engaging in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military would
continue to fight Muslim rebels who engage in criminal activities
despite the signing of a general ceasefire agreement, Chief of
Staff of the Armed Forces Arnulfo Acedera said today.
</P>
<P>
Criminal activities such as kidnapping, harassment and
hijacking are "hostile acts", Acedera said.
</P>
<P>
The truce deal, signed by the government and the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF), took effect on July 21.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he said, the military was willing to pull out
its troops based in various MILF camps captured by the military as
soon as peace and order returns to Central Mindanao, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the military was waiting for whatever
decision is reached by the peace panels of the government and the
MILF, which are expected to meet on July 30 to set guidelines for
the implementation of the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"If the government troops in the said areas are not needed
anymore, they will be recalled and reassigned to other areas," he
said, adding that there is no need for additional troops to be
sent to Mindanao and the repositioning of troops.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member separatist group which has been
fighting government troops in the southern Philippines.  
</P>
