<HEADLINE> India Develops Freon Substitute for Refrigerators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- India has developed a chemical
which can be used as substitute for freon in air conditioners and
refrigerators but will not destroy the earth's ozone shield, Press
Trust of India (PTI) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The chemical called HFC-134a will replace currently used
freon-12 gas, which is blamed for breaking up the ozone layer that
protects humankind from the sun's harmful ultraviolet radiation.
</P>
<P>
Under a United Nations convention on climate change to which
India is a party, all nations are expected to switch over to
ozone-friendly refrigerators by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
There are only five companies in the world that have the
know-how to make the freon substitute and the technology can be
purchased for 25 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Institute of Chemical Technology based in Hyderabad,
Andhra Pradesh, developed HFC-134a on its own, therefore saving
India a huge amount of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The chemical will soon be ready for commercial production in
the country, PTI said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
