<HEADLINE> IMF Praises UK Labor's "Excellent Start" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) today praised the British government for establishing tight
monetary and fiscal policy, but called for broadening of
value-added tax.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at the end of 10 days of discussions with the
Treasury and the Bank of England, the IMF said "the new government
has made an excellent start."
</P>
<P>
"It has set a high standard for its economic policies, aiming
to maintain stability and foster long-term growth while seeking
fairness and developing human potential," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
"And it has taken decisive steps toward these goals by making
the Bank of England independent, introducing a budget that makes
rapid strides toward sound public finances, and initiating
welfare-to-work and other programs to enhance employability," the
IMF said.
</P>
<P>
But the fund warned the financial markets might be
overestimating the increase in interest rates required to attain
the government's inflation target.
</P>
<P>
"With output now close to potential and the associated risks of
rekindling inflation, the economy faces a period of increased
uncertainty. However, the fiscal and monetary policies should
alleviate these tensions significantly," it added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said that chancellor Gordon Brown's Budget earlier this
month did more to get monetary and fiscal policy in balance than
was "sometimes supposed".
</P>
<P>
"While the budget measures could have been tilted more heavily
against current consumer spending, particularly in view of earlier
cuts in income tax, it is difficult to criticize the magnitude of
the overall up-front fiscal correction," the fund said.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF criticized Brown's adoption of the "golden
rule", in which the government is allowed to borrow to cover its
investment.
</P>
<P>
It said the government should aim to balance books completely
to release extra resources for private investment.
</P>
<P>
The IMF welcomed Brown's decision to abolish the tax credit on
dividend payments for some shareholders, and his announcement of
reviews on corporate and capital gains taxes and pensions.
</P>
<P>
But it urged the government to reconsider its refusal to extend
value-added tax to a wider range of goods.
</P>
<P>
Together with the Organization for Economic Co-operation and
Development, the IMF is regarded as one of most authoritative
analysts of economic policy worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
