<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE's New Labor Law Ensures Jobs for Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
published here today a draft labor law in a bid to reverse the
trend of hiring foreign labors rather than nationals by its
booming private sector.
</P>
<P>
The new labor law, carried by the Arabic newspaper Al Bayan
pending endorsement by the union cabinet, requires the country's
private sector to give priority to employing nationals instead of
expatriates.
</P>
<P>
"recruitment of non-nationals in the private sector will not be
allowed unless it is proved that there are no jobless UAE
nationals who can do the same work given to non-nationals," said
the law.
</P>
<P>
This is seen as a further step of the campaign launched earlier
by the UAE authorities to nationalize jobs, ease dependence on
expatriate labor and ensure jobs for its increasing university
graduates.
</P>
<P>
While there was progress in the employment of nationals in the
public sector, the private sector has been reluctant to employ
nationals on the grounds that they lack experience, work fewer
hours and demand far higher salaries than expatriates.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, the Labor and Social Affairs Ministry
will also be authorized to cancel labor permits granted to
non-nationals in some cases, especially when there is a local
worker who is qualified to do that job, the law said.
</P>
<P>
Special sections would be set up at government labor offices in
the country's seven emirates to supervise the implementation of
the law in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates, locals account for around 20 percent of
the nearly 50,000 civil servants but less than 10 percent of the
private workforce.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 90 percent of the UAE labor force are foreigners and
more than half of employees in the private sector are expatriates
from India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and the Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Speed up Infrastructure Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital will undertake
a group of large infrastructural projects in the next five years,
including water, heating and natural gas supply pipeline,
expressways, subways and wastewater treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will speed up construction of the third phase of the
No.9 Waterworks in the second half of this year, and is preparing
to build a new waterworks, according to Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin.
</P>
<P>
The laying of a natural gas pipeline will be completed later
this year to enable Beijing residents to use clean gas piped in
from north China's Changqing gas field early next year, Jia said
at a recent meeting of the city officials.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will speed up the building of a subway line running
through the city's heart, Tiananmen Square, so that it can be open
to traffic in 1999 -- the 50th anniversary of the founding of New
China, he said.
</P>
<P>
A 28-kilometer subway running through Beijing's urban area
north to south and another subway from Xizhimen to the Summer
Palace, a world-famous scenic spot, will also be built in five
years.
</P>
<P>
Also, expressways linking the Badaling Section of the Great
Wall in north Beijing, the Capital Airport and roads to be link
to the Beijing-Tianjin Expressway will be constructed.
</P>
<P>
"Construction of infrastructure should be in tune with fast
development of Beijing," the mayor said. "The infrastructure will
greatly improve the city's investment environment as well."
</P>
</TEXT>
