<HEADLINE> UAE Freezes Bank Accounts of Suspected Drug Dealers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The UAE Central Bank has frozen
bank accounts of eight people suspected of involvement in drug
trafficking, officials from the bank said today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank instructed commercial banks to freeze the
accounts of five UAE-based Indians, a Pakistani, a Zambian woman
and a UAE national as well as their companies, they said.
</P>
<P>
The instruction was triggered by the five persons' alleged
involvement in narcotic pill factories which were busted by
police in Dubai last month, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The freeze came after the publication this month of a draft law
on money laundering, giving UAE authorities greater access to bank
accounts and allowing them to freeze the funds of drug suspects.
</P>
<P>
The draft law, which is to be ratified by the Federal Cabinet,
followed a surge in narcotic trafficking in the country by
international gangs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
