<HEADLINE> Soeharto Urges Monetary Sector to Keep Rupiah's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today called on the country's monetary authorities to make efforts
to keep the stability of rupiah which has plunged to a record low
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The president made the call after hearing report of Finance
Minister Mar'ie Mohamad about the monetary situation in the
country at the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
"There is no new policy in the monetary sector, we still carry
out the controlled float rate," Mar'ie said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said today's spot rupiah against the U.S. dollar
recovered to 2,600:1 from 2,650:1 on Monday following the Central
Bank's intervention.
</P>
<P>
Currency speculators in the country continued their relentless
attack against the rupiah, pushing it to a record low of
2,650/55:1 dollar on Monday morning from 2,510/20 open before
easing to 2,636/41 at 6 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Speculative attacks on the rupiah escalated early last week
following the de facto devaluation of the Thai baht earlier this
month and the Philippine peso on July 11.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank was promoted Monday to raise its daily fixing
of the U.S. dollar-rupiah intervention band by one point to
2,378/2,382 rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The central bank intervened in the market with some 500 million
U.S. dollars through four or five brokers.
</P>
<P>
The government is optimistic that the condition will be better
because Indonesia's economic fundamental is strong, Mar'ie said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank on July 11 had widened the dollar-rupiah
intervention band to 12 percent from 8 percent to avert
speculative attacks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
