<HEADLINE> Taylor Emerges Winner of Liberian Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Former warlord Charles Taylor seems
to have emerged as the winner of Saturday's Liberian election,
with an overwhelming 65 percent majority by votes counted so far.
</P>
<P>
By Monday evening, reports reaching here said of the about two
thirds of the votes counted, Taylor enjoyed a comfortable lead of
65 percent.
</P>
<P>
His close rival, Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, won only 15 of the
votes.
</P>
<P>
Though the final results are expected not to come out before
Wednesday evening, observers believe that Taylor has actually won
the election, making a run-off unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
In contemplating her defeat, Johnson-Sirleaf, the former
senior official of the United Nations has accused the west
African peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG of influencing voters
at polling stations.
</P>
<P>
She made the allegation while addressing her supporters on
Monday in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
International observers of the election, however, agreed that
the election is free and fair.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference Monday afternoon in Monrovia,
former U.S. president Jimmy Carter praised, on behalf of the
observers, the conduct of the election and the large turnout of
voters.
</P>
<P>
He did admit that there were minor problems, but said they are
not enough to influence the results of the election. Carter that
any complaints should be filed to the Independent Electoral
Commission for investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
