<HEADLINE> Australian Shares Close Slightly Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares clawed their
way to a slightly firmer close today, with anxious investors
sidelined ahead of tonight's testimony from Chairman of the U.S.
Federal Reserve Bank Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's testimony to the Congress and the local release of
the consumer price index tomorrow both give indications on future
interest rate movements.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended 3.0 points higher at 2,656.4,
but just shy of an intraday high of 2,657.3.
</P>
<P>
"It was just very quiet, everybody is waiting to see what
Greenspan says and what CPI (consumer price index) does tomorrow,"
BNP Investment Management's Anton Tagliaferro said.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 239.72 million shares traded worth
559.0 million Australian dollars (413.66 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index increased 15.8 points to 4,248.9,
while the all resources index slipped 8.4 points to 1,418.3.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate sensitive banking and insurance stocks gained
ground, underpinned by optimism that inflation and wages data due
out this week will pave the way for a further cut in official
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank jumped 20 cents, NAB increased eight cents,
ANZ Bank was up 1.5 cents and Westpac Bank was unchanged at 7.98
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index tumbled 17.5 points to 1,294.2, while gold
bullion closed at 325.5 US dollars an ounce down from 327.95
Monday.  
</P>
