<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Outside US-initiated African Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, the largest contributor to
African peace-keeping, has been barred from taking part in the
African Quick Reaction Force initiated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
With the arrival of U.S. military trainers in Senegal and
Uganda on Sunday, which many observers say is a prelude to the
U.S. initiative proposed last year, Nigeria is seen out of the
list of seven African countries the U.S. soldiers are scheduled
to head for.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military personnel will be in Senegal and Uganda for
two months to train the soldiers designed for the force, mooted
by the U.S. last year. They will then go to Tunisia, Mali,
Ethiopia, Malawi and Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said that Nigeria was barred from
participating in the force because it is not a "democratic
country".
</P>
<P>
No official reaction has been made to the training plan for
the U.S.-initiated African intervention force. But military
sources have expressed the government view that it is impossible
for a pan-African peace-keeping force without Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The military administration in Abuja has been advocating for
the establishment of a continental peace-keeping force with the
west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) as the nucleus.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG, whose successful mission has ensured a peaceful
conduct of elections last Saturday in war-ravaged Liberia, is led
by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The force is also in Sierra Leone ready for restoring the
country's civilian government overthrown by a military coup on
May 25.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the arrival of 60 U.S. trainers in
Senegal was without fanfare. None of the country's daily
newspapers, including the government-owned, published news of the
arrival.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the seven countries included in the U.S. military's
itinerary, no other African countries have expressed support for
the planned intervention force.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela had last year berated
the U.S. initiative, saying it should be the United Nations'
prerogative.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has expressed concern that the initiative would allow
outsiders, especially the U.S. to have authority over how and
when African countries deploy their forces.
</P>
<P>
The South African government reportedly restated its objection
to the initiative on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
