<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Liuzhou Builds Flood-Control Dyke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The industrial city of
Liuzhou, in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, is
building a permanent flood-control embankment along the Liujiang
River.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that the main streets of Liuzhou are 85-95
meters above the sea level. Without any form of flood control in
place, severe flooding that might occur within the next 20 years
could submerge many industrial and mining enterprises in the city,
the data show.
</P>
<P>
An exceptionally fierce flood in July, 1994 forced 90 percent
of Liuzhou's factories to suspend operation and inundated half of
the city.
</P>
<P>
A city official said Liuzhou's flood-control project
consists of dykes, sluice gates, lock gates and water pumps. The
embankment under construction is 16.62 kilometers and has 22
sluice gates and 20 water pumping stations.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the dyke, scheduled for completion in the year
2000, will cost 1.2 billion yuan. As part of the work, 160,000 sq
m of housing in the area will be removed, and more than 120,000
people will be displaced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
