<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- After the revelation of the audit on public finance, the
French government announced on Monday its plan of readjustment
aimed at reducing by 32 billion francs (about 5.3 billion
U.S. dollars) of France's public deficit to respect the criteria
of Maastricht treaty on single currency. Even though the strict
objective of cutting the deficit to 3 percent of the gross
domestic product will be postponed until 1998, the plan was
welcomed by the European Commission and the German government.
</P>
<P>
-- France and Spain reaffirmed on Monday their will to work
together in the fight against terrorism perpetrated by the Basque
separatist movement ETA. At the annual meeting of the two interior
ministers, Spain asked France to arrest the leading figures of the
ETA who Madrid believes are hiding in France. Madrid also asked
Paris to extradite Luis Alvarez Santacristina, a former leader of
the ETA who was arrested in France in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The center-right opposition on Monday strongly reacted to
the announcement by the government of the plan of readjustment to
reduce public deficit. Nicolas Sarkozy, the spokesman of the
Gaullist Rally for the Republic, accused the government of
incoherence in its policy-making.
</P>
<P>
-- The Cambodian royalist forces of Prince Norodom Ranariddh
Monday failed in their attempt to recapture the strategic base of
Samrong in northern Cambodia. At least 20,000 villagers of Samrong
have fled to a frontier town in the Province of Surin in Thailand
over the past several days as fighting went on between the
royalist forces and the forces of Hun Sen, said international
humanitarian organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
