<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weaker As Markets Trade Quiet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
marginally weaker today as markets await the release of quarterly
inflation and wages figures.
</P>
<P>
The June quarter consumer price index (CPI) from the Australian
Bureau of Statistics is due tomorrow, while key quarterly wages
figures are due Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 74.08 US cents from 74.13 at
Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Australian dollar had begun the day in a
weaker mood after falling in sympathy with the New Zealand dollar.
</P>
<P>
The CPI report is expected to bolster the argument for a cut to
the 5.5 percent cash rate by the Central Bank in the short term.
</P>
<P>
"The market has factored in a very good CPI, an okay wages
number and a rate cut in the next couple of weeks, so it just
depends now on what the data brings out," said Rory Robertson from
Bankers Trust of Australia.
</P>
<P>
On cross-rates, the Australian dollar finished at 86.16 from
85.66 against Japanese yen and was at 1.3363 up from 1.3278
against the German mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
