<HEADLINE> Thailand to Turn Phuket Into Regional Trading Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 22 (Xinhua) -- About 15 billion baht (500 million
US dollars) will be spent to turn Phuket Island, in the south of
Thailand, into a duty-free international port serving Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh has asked the National
Economic and Social Development Board, the state planning agency,
to complete a masterplan to turn the island into a port along the
lines of Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The plan, initiated by the previous government, also envisages
the popular resort island becoming an international convention
center, a regional hub of trading and business, and a center for
human resource development.
</P>
<P>
Projects already under construction include garbage treatment,
waste water treatment, and environmental restoration in seaside
resorts.
</P>
<P>
Expansion of main roads, improvements to the deep-sea port,
construction of three piers for tourist vessels and airport
upgrading are also planned.
</P>
<P>
Other projects under consideration are preservation of mangrove
forests, a marine-life sanctuary and a mineral museum.
</P>
<P>
Phuket, about 860 kilometers south of Bangkok, is known as the
Pearl of the South. With a total area of 540 square kilometers, it
is the country's largest island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
