<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Displaces 200,000 People in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Recent heavy fighting in
northern Afghanistan has brought the number of displaced people
entering the capital city Kabul since the beginning of this year
to 200,000.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued here today by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), several thousands
more are believed to be scattered across the northern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
During the seven days leading up to July 20, the release said,
a UNHCR monitoring post north of Kabul recorded 15,474 displaced
people entering Kabul from the north.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest rate over a similar period since
mid-January, when 47,000 were displaced from the same area in a
week.
</P>
<P>
The latest sharp increase in the number of displaced people was
the result of intense fighting, in which the Taliban militia lost
the key town of Charikar, about 65 kilometers north of Kabul, to
the anti-Taliban alliance, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The alliance also recaptured the strategic air base of Bagram,
some 40 kilometers north of Kabul, in its attack last Saturday
night against the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The release said that most of those who arrived in Kabul last
week were among the last remaining inhabitants of Charikar itself.
</P>
<P>
The town, which is believed to have had somewhere between
100,000 and 150,000 inhabitants a year ago, is now reported to be
largely deserted by civilian inhabitants, said the release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Exports Likely to Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The insolvency of the Kia Group and
the currency crisis in the Southeast Asian region will likely deal
a harsh blow to South Korea's exports in the second half of the
year, the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the country's exports will suffer
greatly in the latter half, as it may take a long time for the
ailing Kia to normalize operations.
</P>
<P>
The Kia Group had forecast its sales and exports at 21.8
billion U.S. dollars and 4.5 billion dollars respectively for this
year.
</P>
<P>
However, in the process of taking steps to regain managerial
normalcy, with the government's financial support, Kia's sales and
exports are expected to decline, said ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the ongoing Thai baht crisis, which has spread to
other Southeast Asian countries like the Philippines, Indonesia and
Malaysia, is expected to hurt the exports of South Korean
enterprises operating in the region, including the Kia group.
</P>
</TEXT>
