<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Violence Drops in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Political violence in South
Africa has plummeted, the country's independent Human Rights
Commission said in a report issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The commission said in its annual report for 1996 that it had
identified many positive signs three years after the first
all-race general elections brought the black majority to power in
1994.
</P>
<P>
"Paramount is the decline in political violence for the third
consecutive year to the lowest total recorded in our existence,"
the commission said.
</P>
<P>
It said 1,057 people died in all forms of political violence
in 1996, down from 1,296 in 1995 and from a peak of 4,406 in
1993.
</P>
<P>
The commission said in a separate monthly report for May that
although 340 people died in all forms of political violence in
the first five months of this year,the monthly average for 1997
was down to 68 from 81.5 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But the commission noted that non-political crime and violence
are still high since apartheid was lifted.
</P>
<P>
The commission was set up in 1988 to monitor violence and
human rights in the struggle over apartheid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
