<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Consults Mubarak before Talking with Levy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat
today paid a lightning visit to Egypt today to consult President
Hosni Mubarak before going to Brussels for talks with Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian MENA news agency reported that Arafat flew to the
Mediterranean city of Alexandria for a brief meeting with Mubarak
this morning on his way to the Belgian capital.
</P>
<P>
The two Arab leaders are expected to explore the possibility to
galvanize the peace process paralyzed in March by Israel's
obstinate building of thousands of homes for Jewish settlers in
East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as their future
capital.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mubarak meeting will be followed up by an enlarged
Egyptian-Palestinian meeting in Cairo on Sunday to evaluate the
present situation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt brokered three meetings between Palestinian National
Authority top negotiator Nabil Sha'ath and Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai in Tel Aviv last week and is expected
to host a tripartite summit among Mubarak, Arafat and Jordan's
King Hussein before the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Later today, Arafat is due in Belgium to meet with Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy, which is part a European bid to
advance the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace moves.
</P>
<P>
European officials said earlier they did not want the
Arafat-Levy meeting to be superficial and hoped the two sides
could agree on confidence-building measures, mainly to provide aid
to the ailing Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, Arafat will also meet with foreign ministers of
the European Union (EU), who are there to attend the
organization's General Affairs Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa welcomed the rising
European mediation role on Monday, expressing hope that Arafat's
meeting with EU ministers could achieve progress.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace march has been deadlocked for
four months, with violence raging in both West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, however, refused
to give a temporary halt to the settlement expansion, a
prerequisite the Palestinians insist on for resumption of talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
