<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down On Oil Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Customs has pledged to
tighten its control on the smuggling of oil products, which has
been on the rise since the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, Chinese Customs solved 41 smuggling cases
involving 62,000 tons, or 133 million yuan-worth, of oil products.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the weakened international oil prices, oil
smuggling has run rampant since March. Ocean transport is the main
means of moving the illegal goods, so Customs officials have
tightened their checks in coastal provinces of Guangdong, Guangxi,
Fujian and Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
A recent national anti-smuggling conference initiated by the
Chinese Customs has called for coastal customs officers to
examine all oil tanks which dock at Chinese ports.
</P>
<P>
Police are expected to patrol coastal seas 24 hours a day and
oil tankers must be checked ship by ship. 
</P>
