<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Army Extends Amnesty for Deserters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's army authorities have
decided to extend a declared amnesty, which was effective from
July 10 to Monday midnight, till midnight Saturday, a military
spokesman said here today .
</P>
<P>
During the 11-day amnesty, the fifth in the war-torn island
country since 1995, about 3,000 deserters had reportedly returned
for duty, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the army authorities had decided to extend the
amnesty at the request of many parents and relatives of deserters.
</P>
<P>
Unless they report back by July 26 or Saturday, they will be
arrested by the military police and the civil police and be tried
by Court Martial with severe punishment, the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
Those who return before Saturday will not be punished and will
be entitled to their earlier held ranks and pay with effect from
the date of reporting.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 had deserted the army in the country over the
past 20 years, according to local newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
The army authorities had offered amnesty for deserters on four
previous occasions since 1995 and more than 10,000 deserters had
returned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
