<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Position on Privatization Reaffirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean Minister has
reaffirmed the government's commitment to selling off
parastatals, but said the process is dragging because the
majority of Zimbabweans are still poor and the policy is new.
</P>
<P>
Minister of state in the President's Office Cephas Msipa said
this on Monday when he gave a keynote address to senior
management of hotel giant, Zimbabwe Sun, which is holding its
annual conference at the Great Zimbabwe Hotel in Masvingo of
south Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
''That is why we are having to go through the process of
commercialization first so that we shade them off on a strong
financial base,'' Msipa noted.
</P>
<P>
He added, ''the reason why we are taking time is that the
majority of Zimbabweans have no money, and that this is new
territory for us. We do not want a situation where the same
people who already own something will earn more.''
</P>
<P>
The minister said indigenization is a process aimed at
democratizing the economic system and promoting human rights --
''such as the right to employment, the right to own property and
the right to earn an equitable standard of living''.
</P>
<P>
''Our aim is to develop a strong domestic sector which can be
the engine for economic growth,'' said Msipa.
</P>
<P>
''The overall objective is to promote more wealth and
employment, reduce poverty and restore self respect and dignity
to the majority of Zimbabweans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the rise in crime could be linked to
rising unemployment. 
</P>
