<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Female Corpse Unearthed in Downtown Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- An ancient corpse with clearly
distinguishable features was recently unearthed from a
construction site in downtown Shanghai, giving residents of
China's most bustling city an idea of what one of their ancestors
looked like.
</P>
<P>
The female corpse, said to be some 400-500 years old, is
believed to be the oldest well-preserved corpse ever excavated in
Shanghai. She was found in one of 14 tombs located in the
construction site of a middle school building in Luwan District,
according to Monday's Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
The report described the corpse, dressed in silk clothing and
probably aged 40, as being "preserved so perfectly that her joints
can move and her muscle tissue is not stiff; the rarest thing is
that her nose is still intact and her features are easily
identified."
</P>
<P>
Ancient corpse researcher Xu Yongqing said the body, possibly
from the middle years of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), was found
in a pool of fragrant, coffee-colored fluid when her coffin was
opened.
</P>
<P>
Moisture usually leads to the rapid decay of a buried
body. Mummies previously found in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region were all preserved under extremely dry
conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Such a kind of ancient corpse is very rare, mostly found in
east China's Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces and the Shanghai
area," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
"It is because of the airtight coffin and the fluid which was
able to destroy harmful microorganisms that the corpse was so well
preserved," explained Xu, author of "Chinese Ancient Corpses."
</P>
<P>
The corpse has been sent to the Shanghai Museum of Natural
History. But the newspaper did not say how the corpse is currently
being stored.
</P>
<P>
The museum where Xu works is China's leading research institute
of ancient corpses, keeping more than 20 ancient human bodies. It
is conducting a study of ancient corpses in the Shanghai area
jointly with the Chinese University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The discovery provides precious materials for our research,"
Xu said.
</P>
<P>
The tombs, the most complete family tomb complex ever found in
Shanghai, are said to belong to a wealthy family which lived
during the Ming Dynasty. A golden coronet also was unearthed from
the tomb.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
