<HEADLINE> Food Plan Launched in Famine-stricken Eastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A new plan to boost food
production, storage and marketing has been launched in
famine-stricken Kamuli District, eastern Uganda, "The Monitor"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, locals have an obligation to produce food
to support themselves but not for cash, and every homestead must
have three granaries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at a function chaired by Coordinator of
Political Activities in the Resident District Commissioner's
Office that production and marketing committees are to be formed
at local councils to coordinate food and cash crop production.
</P>
<P>
The function also called schools, health units and sub-county
headquarters to plant banana and coffee, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is an important local cash crop. Local people use
banana as one of the many kinds of their staple food.
</P>
<P>
Kamuli is one of the 19 famine-stricken districts during this
dry season among a total of 45 districts in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The present famine is caused by drought. Kotido, the most
productive agricultural district in the area, has witnessed one
of the worst food outputs in many years. Crops like millet,
maize, sorghum and cassava are dying, and nomads are moving their
cattle to seek for water and greener pastures in the district.
</P>
</TEXT>
