<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Relief Agency to Move to Gaza Strip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Relief and
Works Agency (UNRWA) has decided to move its headquarters from
Vienna, the capital of Austria, to Gaza Strip, according to a
report of The Jerusalem Times today.
</P>
<P>
The relocation of UNRWA headquarters is in response to a call
by the U.N. General Assembly to shift the agency to the field of
operations proper as soon as possible, said Peter Hansen,
Commissioner of UNRWA for Palestine Refugees in the Near East.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that UNRWA moves headquarters in its
47-year-old history. In 1978, owing to the unstable conditions in
Lebanon, UNRWA moved its headquarters to Vienna, where it has
remained for the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
Hansen told reporters in Gaza that the official opening of the
new headquarters will take place in August, adding that there was
full co-ordination between UNRWA and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) in various sectors.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, UNRWA has funded the construction of 20
schools in Gaza Strip to accommodate the children of the
refugees, and has invested in the restoration work of over 2,000
homes in the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
Hansen pledged that his organization will continue to offer
its services to Palestinian refugees wherever they are found.
</P>
<P>
"In July 1994, (former) U.N. Secretary General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali announced that UNRWA headquarters would be shifted
to Gaza as part of the support extended by the United Nations to
the peace process," Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
By moving its headquarters from Vienna to Gaza, UNRWA expects
to save large sums of money. This is especially important as UNRWA
expects a large deficit in its 1996 budget.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 members of personnel will be relocated from Vienna to
Gaza, many of them Palestinians. Another 80 people from Gaza Strip
are to join the staff.
</P>
<P>
UNRWA was established on December 8, 1949 in accordance with a
U.N. General Assembly decision. It draws its funds mainly from
various governments, governmental and non-governmental
organizations and private contributions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
