<HEADLINE> Kenya's External Debt Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's external debt stood at
350 billion Kenyan Shillings (about 6 billion U.S. Dollars) as of
March 1997, according to the latest issue of the Economic Review
available here today.
</P>
<P>
The monthly review issued by the Central Bank of Kenya said
that the debt amounts had declined during the past two years,
falling from 380 billion Shillings in December 1995 to 360
billion Shillings in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
It noted that out of the current debts, 200 billion Shillings
was owed to multilateral institutions, accounting for 57 percent
of the total debts while bilateral debts stood at 130 billion
Shillings representing 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce external debt, the review said, the Kenyan
government has increased domestic budget financing by the issue
of floating rate Treasury Bonds.
</P>
<P>
This year, the government has launched the third and fourth
issues of floating rate Treasury Bonds in April and June
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The review noted that the 11 months of the 1996/97 fiscal year
indicated a higher budget deficit at 10.3 billion Shillings
compared with 9 billion Shillings during the same period of
fiscal year 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was negatively impacted by interest payment on
government debt which was on the increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
