<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ice Jam Control Project On China's Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The disastrous ice jams that
plagued the lower reaches of China's Yellow River, the country's
second longest, throughout history will no longer pose a threat
when the Xiaolangdi water control project is completed in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The multi-purpose project, which has a storage capacity of 12.6
billion cubic meters, including two billion cubic meters designed
to prevent ice jams, will combine with the Sanmenxia, Guxian and
Luhun reservoirs to control ice jams on the river's upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
Ice jams have long been a problem for the lower reaches. From
1855 to 1955, there were problems with ice every five years, and
it was considered even more destructive than summer floods.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments have done heir utmost to
solve the ice problem since the founding of new China in
1949. Breaking the ice up was one preventive measure, but the
river is so long and the water and ice are discharged in such
large amounts that it was not the most efficient way to deal with
the problem.
</P>
<P>
The river originates on the Loess Plateau and travels eastward
through central China's Henan province, then changes its course
and moves northeastward. This contributes to the ice problem in
the early spring when ice and water are discharged from the upper
reaches, while the lower reaches are still frozen.
</P>
<P>
The Sanmenxia Reservoir is the first key water control project
on the Yellow river and has been successful in controlling ice
jams by regulating water flow. But, power plants on the upper
reaches meant a larger water flow, and as a result, the 1.8
billion cu m capacity was not sufficient to contain the ice and
water.
</P>
<P>
Last January, an ice jam hit Liangshan County in east China's
Shandong province, where the river turns southward again, and
in Taiqian County in central China's Henan province, inundating
6,000 ha of farmland and affecting 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
This menace is expected to disappear when the Xiaolangdi Dam
is completed in the early 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Defends Decision to Admit Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) today defended its decision to
admit Myanmar, saying the move provides an opportunity to
"continue interacting with them."
</P>
<P>
"It is better to engage with them," Abdullah Ahmad Badawi,
chairman of the ASEAN Standing Committee and foreign minister of
Malaysia, told a press conference here today. "The best way to
engage with them is to get them inside the club as early as
possible."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Myanmar's admission into the grouping was
"a consensus decision" by the foreign ministers of the ASEAN
countries and the ASEAN can benefit from whatever cooperation it
will have with Myanmar as a group or on a bilateral basis.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, together with Laos, will officially become members of
the regional grouping tomorrow, thus boosting the number of ASEAN
members from seven to nine and marking a step closer toward the
organization's dream of including all the 10 Southeast Asian
countries in its membership.
</P>
<P>
"Engaging Myanmar continually as of now will be good for all of
us," Abdullah Ahmad Badawi declared.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN, which presently groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, decided in May
to admit Myanmar simultaneously with Laos and Cambodia over
criticism from some Western countries, but it later deferred
Cambodia's entry to a later date because of the factional fighting
in the country.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony will be held for the admission in this township near
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia's capital, tomorrow when the national flags
of Myanmar and Laos will be raised.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
