<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, WWF to Hold Seminar on Traditional Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The first international symposium
on traditional Chinese medicine and wildlife conservation in
Australia is to be held on August 4 in Sydney, it was announced
today.
</P>
<P>
The symposium will "build crucial bridges of communication and
understanding between local Chinese community and the government
in Australia," the World Wide Fund For Nature (WWF) Australia and
Trade Record Analysis of Fauna and Flora In Commerce (TRAFFIC)
Oceania said today.
</P>
<P>
In co-hosting this symposium, the Australian government is the
first of the 139 parties to the Convention on International Trade
in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) to answer
the call from the recent meeting in Harare to work more closely
with traditional Chinese medicine practitioners and users, the WWF
Australia said.
</P>
<P>
The practice of traditional Chinese medicine is growing in
Australia and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
There are now approximately 4,500 Chinese medicinal
practitioners in Australia, a number forecast to double by the
year 2000. Currently 2.8 million consultations are conducted each
year, with an annual turnover of at least 62 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"With the increasing popularity of traditional Chinese medicine
in Australia, there is an urgent need to inform the practitioners,
traders and users of traditional Chinese medicine about the issue,
the rationale behind CITES and the relevant Australian law, and
the proper procedure for importing products into Australia," said
Samuel Lee of TRAFFIC East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The symposium is jointly organized by TRAFFIC Oceania,
Environment Australia and the University of Western Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Fishermen Continue Holding U.S. Ferry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian fishermen continued to
hold the U.S. ferry Malaspina captive at Prince Rupert, British
Columbia (B.C.), for a third day today, despite a court injunction
calling for its release.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Fisheries Minister David Anderson have arrived in the
northern B.C. coast community, some 1,500 kilometers northwest of
Vancouver, in a bid to free the U.S. ferry.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen, frustrated by the lack of action of the federal
government, took the action themselves to protest the U.S. state
of Alaska's overfishing of Canadian-bound sockeye.
</P>
<P>
Despite that the Alaskan government obtained an injunction from
a Canadian federal court Sunday ordering the end of the blockade,
there has been little effect.
</P>
<P>
And new Canadian fishing boats and pleasure boats have joined
the siege today at the port.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen said they will not let the ferry go unless those
named in the injunction not be held responsible for any blockage
damages.
</P>
<P>
Tension began to rise in Prince Rupert on Friday after the
United States admitted it had caught more than three times its
limit of sockeye that spawn in Canadian rivers.
</P>
<P>
On Friday night, dozens of Canadian fishing boats surrounded
two U.S. salmon vessels to prevent them from delivering their
catch. And one U.S. boat collided with a Canadian vessel.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, an estimated 200 boats surrounded the Alaskan
state ferry carrying about 300 passengers, preventing it from
leaving port.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen said they wanted Anderson to restart the salmon
talks with the U.S. and allow northern B.C. fishermen to increase
their take of sockeye.
</P>
<P>
They also wanted transit fees imposed on all U.S. marine
traffic along B.C.'s northern coast.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing salmon war between Canada and the United States
started after the failure of negotiations over revisions to the
Pacific Salmon Treaty of 1985, which set salmon catches for both
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0182 </DOCNO>
