<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Promote Services Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is launching
its first ever campaign to promote the services industry in an
effort to boost foreign exchange revenue, local newspaper the
Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Narongchai Akrasanee said that the "Thai
Services Trade Promotion" program has been designed to increase
the direct export of services, promote the expansion of Thai
franchises overseas and modernize the industry through the
acquisition of new technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The program will feature five sectors -- restaurants,
entertainment, amusement parks and golf courses, beauty and health
care and medical care, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government is hoping that the services industry will boost
the foreign exchange revenue entering the country, which is facing
a severe economic slowdown, the Nation said.
</P>
<P>
The program is also seen as part of the preparation for trade
liberalization under the World Trade Organization, according to
the minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that eight action plans had been drawn up to promote
and develop the five services sectors.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the ministry see tremendous foreign exchange
earnings potential in the services industry, particularly Thai
restaurants and music, which are popular abroad due to their
unique attributes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
