<HEADLINE> Costa Rican President to Visit Mercosur Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican President Jose Maria
Figueres is planning a tour to Mercosur (Southern Common Market)
countries soon to establish closer ties with the trade bloc,
Foreign Trade Minister Jose Manuel Salazar said today.
</P>
<P>
The president's trip to the Mercosur member countries --
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, is part of Costa Rica's
development strategy, Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
The creation of a Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA)
scheduled for the year 2005 has contributed to closer relations
between Central and South American countries, the minister said at
a seminar on Costa Rica's growth strategies.
</P>
<P>
Central American countries have few trade relations with South
America so far, he added.
</P>
<P>
This year, Costa Rica is the president in rotation of the FTAA
coordinating body and will host a ministerial meeting next year to
analyze the progress of the process.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Vice President Rodrigo Oreamuno said that his
country's exports are expected to reach 5 billion U.S. dollars
next year which was the initial goal set by President Figueres for
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Oreamuno said that the Costa Rican government has reduced
inflation and interest rates to attract foreign investments.
