<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Indonesia Intervenes as Rupiah Plunges to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Currency speculators in Indonesia
continued their relentless attack against the rupiah Monday,
pushing it to a record low and prompting the central bank to
intervene to defend the currency.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said today spot rupiah against the U.S. dollar dipped
to a historic low of 2,650/55 Monday morning from 2,510/20 open
before easing to 2,636/41 at 6:00 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia, the central bank, was forced to raise its daily
fixing of the U.S. dollar-rupiah intervention band by one point to
2,378/2,382 rupiah, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
According to a Bank Indonesia official, the intervention was to
calm foreign exchange markets following the rupiah's fall in
value.
</P>
<P>
"We did it just to calm down the market ... I hope it
(speculative action) will not continue," said Djakaria, head of
the central bank's Foreign Exchange Division.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia Governor Soedradjad Djiwandono called on the
people Monday not to panic about the steep fall in the rupiah's
exchange rate and not to join the rush to the American dollar.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the rupiah became the target of speculators Monday
after being spared previously when they focused on other regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
"They are trying to force the central bank to float the rupiah
or at least widen the intervention band because they have been
long on dollar and short on rupiah," a dealer with a local foreign
exchange bank said.
</P>
<P>
"If they could force the Thai baht and the Philippine peso to
devalue by more than 15 percent, why not the rupiah?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia on July 11 widened the dollar-rupiah
intervention band to 12 percent from 8 percent to avert
speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
Speculative attacks on the rupiah escalated early last week
following the de facto devaluation of the Thai baht earlier this
month and the Philippine peso on July 11.
</P>
<P>
"The intervention seemed to help calm the market. But the
overall appetite for dollar remains strong. There are still
attempts to test the (intervention) band," a dealer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
