<HEADLINE> Nepali Capital on Clean Campaign for Tourism Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Kathmandu, the capital city of
Nepal, has launched a campaign to make the city cleaner for a
tourism year, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
A measure taken by the authorities is to collect garbage at
night in an effort to boost waste handling.
</P>
<P>
Newly-elected Mayor of Kathmandu Keshab Sthapit said on Monday
that as the Visit Nepal Year' 98 comes near, the municipal
government decided to give more attention to the garbage issue.
</P>
<P>
The work of waste collection at night began on June 19,
covering the downtown area and the major roads of the city, the
local press reported.
</P>
<P>
This new system of garbage collection might turn out to be more
effective because there are less traffic at night, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
With rapid growth in population and an even faster expansion of
the fleet of vehicles, Kathmandu is faced with a serious
environmental problem.
</P>
<P>
In a drive to make the capital cleaner and free from unwanted
animals, a total of 470 stray dogs have been killed so far, the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
And illegally built structures have been demolished, the mayor
added.
</P>
<P>
The mayor also said that an integrated programs will be
launched to improve water supply, traffic, environmental
protection, sewerage and solid waste management in the capital.
</P>
