<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Stepping Up Efforts to Train Labor Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chilean government is
stepping up efforts to train the country's labor force and gain
competitiveness at the increasingly demanding world market.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have been prompted up by Chilean President Eduardo
Frei, who signed, on April 30, a decree to declare a "National
Year of Training" between May 1, 1997 and May 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
On signing the decree, Frei emphasized that training is
fundamental for Chile to become a developed nation, and that
neither individuals nor companies can grow without training.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks later, a National Council on Training was established
to group together government and private sector representatives
and coordinate research into the development of human resources
and the use of tax breaks for training purposes.
</P>
<P>
And this week, the Senate approved a new training and
employment statute that seeks to train 20 percent of the labor
force in the country every year. Last year, only 8.6 percent of
the labor force received training.
</P>
<P>
To provide incentives, the law, which will take effect on
January 1, 1998, offers tax exemptions for businesses which
provide training for their workers.
</P>
<P>
In another effort to expand coverage, a National Training Fund
was created for those who wish to join the labor force training.
</P>
<P>
With a budget that will go up to the equivalent of 29 million
U.S. dollars by 1998, the institution will be able to train more
men, women and adolescents to become workers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the National Training and State Employment Service
(SENCE) is responsible for organizing the training of unemployed
workers and 16-24 year-olds for free.
</P>
<P>
SENCE Director Ignacio Larraechea said his institution has used
a total of more than 660 million dollars to train 4.32 million
people since it was created 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Through the Chilean Youth Program, the SENCE plans to offer
training courses for some 70,000 poor, jobless young people at a
cost of 58 million dollars to the state between 1996 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
And through the School Program for Women (PRODEMU), some
120,000 poor women have received training, and many of them have
already formed their own home businesses and rural shops.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of their training, the women are now aware of
their potentiality and their dignity," said President Frei.
</P>
<P>
The PRODEMU is expected to enroll another 120,000 women this
year to help develop their creativity and give them better chances
to join the country's social, cultural and economic processes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
