<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine's GDP Down 7.5 Percent in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's economy, which has been in
crisis for the last four years, is still contracting with gross
domestic product (GDP) and investment for the first six months of
1997 both down on last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Statistics Ministry last week show
that the country's GDP for the first half of this year was just
under 40 billion karbovanets, (21.8 billion U.S. dollars), down
7.5 percent on the same period in 1996. That comes on top of a 10
percent slide in GDP in 1996 over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The fall was worst in agriculture, transport and communications.
</P>
<P>
Investment also slumped 11 percent, mainly in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's economy has been steadily worsening since
independence in 1991. Industry and agriculture have been hit hard
by the country's transformation from a centrally-planned economy
to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, President Leonid Kuchma, whose reform plans
over the last three years haven't borne fruit, set up a High
Economic Council to speed up reforms.
</P>
<P>
The council will make strategic economic decisions and
implement reforms, including economic liberalization, halving
taxes within year, speeding up privatization and agricultural
reforms and legalizing the vast shadow economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
