<HEADLINE> Thailand to Press for Seoul to Ease Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will press South Korea to
ease trade barriers faced by Thai products.
</P>
<P>
Thai Commerce Minister Narongchai Akrasanee is scheduled to
meet his South Korean counterpart early next month in Seoul to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first meeting between trade ministers of the two
countries for three years.
</P>
<P>
Thai exports to South Korea, mainly food and textiles, face
hefty customs tariffs, tough quarantine standards and complicated
import regulations, according to a Thai Commerce Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
South Korea does not allow the import of rice for direct sale,
only as an ingredient in food processing and tapioca flour is
similarly affected.
</P>
<P>
Imports of frozen shrimps are taxed at 75 percent, frozen squid
30 percent and canned tuna 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Narongchai would also try to persuade South Korea to accept
more Thai frozen chicken and pork.  
</P>
</TEXT>
