<HEADLINE> Siemens Decides to Go Slow in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Siemens AG group, which has
already invested 500 million U.S. dollars in India since 1991,
will slow down its original plan to invest another 500 million
dollars in the country by the year 2000, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The decision to postpone an additional investment of 500
million dollars followed disastrous results recorded by Siemens
India in 1996-97 which made a loss of 800 million rupees (about 23
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Announcing this at a press conference in Berlin Monday, Gunter
Wilhelm, a senior Siemens AG manager for the Asia-Pacific region,
said the adverse business climate in India and the expected losses
in their business activities in the country would pull down their
net profit for the entire Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He complained of a sustained slowdown in India's industrial
growth and delay in implementation of the reform process in key
sectors like telecommunications which resulted in a slump in
demand for Siemens products.
</P>
<P>
Later, Heinrich Pierer, chief executive of the Siemens group
worldwide, noted that the main reason for the adverse business
climate in India was the delay in implementation of policy by the
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
"The problem in India is bureaucracy. You can not wait
endlessly for clearances," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
