<HEADLINE> ASEAN ASC Chairman Proud of Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior official
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) today
expressed satisfaction with the achievements the grouping has made
in the past year.
</P>
<P>
"The last one year had been rather momentous for the
Association as we strove toward further enhancement and
consolidation of intra-ASEAN cooperation in various fields," said
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, chairman of the 30th ASEAN Standing
Committee (ASC) and foreign minister of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In a closing statement at the two-day ASC meeting, Badawi said
the ASC meeting reviewed the progress the ASEAN has made in
political, security and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"An appraisal of the work of the ASC showed that we have
attained encouraging achievements in political and security
cooperation, economic integration efforts as well as in function
cooperation areas and in our relations with dialogue partners," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF), which will have
discussions here later this month, the ASC chairman noted that the
ARF has progressed into an effective multilateral forum for
promoting security dialogue and cooperation in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
"The ARF has played a positive role in enhancing mutual
understanding and trust, promoting greater transparency as well as
strengthening the commitment among participants to maintain peace
and stability in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The ARF is represented by the seven ASEAN member countries --
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam; the ASEAN dialogue partners including Australia,
Canada, China, the European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand,
South Korea, Russia, the U.N. Development Program and the United
States; and the observer countries -- Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar and
Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi pointed out that one of the "major
preoccupations" of his committee in the past year was the "active
preparations" for Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar to join the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
But while Laos and Myanmar will officially become ASEAN members
tomorrow and their foreign ministers are to attend the 30th ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting (AMM) scheduled to start on July 24, the
admission of Cambodia, which the ASEAN had decided to admit as a
full member in May, has been deferred because of the factional
fighting in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ASC chairman told a press conference after the ASC closing
session that Cambodia will retain its observer status and any
change will have to be decided by the ministerial meeting, which
is expected to hear a report from an ASEAN mission sent to meet
Cambodian officials earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The ASC meeting, together with a senior officials meeting, was
held to make preparations for the AMM and the ARF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
