<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papua New Guinea Elects New PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Port Moresby Governor Bill Skate
was today elected Papua New Guinea's (PNG) new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Skate's election, with 71 votes in favor in PNG's 109-seat
parliament, means the return to power of the coalition which held
government before last month's national election, the Australian
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The new ruling alliance includes the country's four major
political parties.
</P>
<P>
Skate, who defeated former Prime Minister Michael Somare 71 to
35, takes over as prime minister from Julius Chan, who lost his
seat in last month's election.
</P>
<P>
John Pundari, member of the former ruling Pangu Party, was
earlier elected parliamentary speaker, defeating a group of
parties and independents headed by Michael Somare.
</P>
<P>
Skate had campaigned strongly against the former Chan
government, accusing it of corruption and condemning its
controversial plan to use mercenaries to quell a secessionist
rebellion on Bougainville island.
</P>
<P>
Skate is the first ethnic Papuan to serve as prime minister
since PNG's independence in 1975. Papua is a region in the south
of PNG's mainland.
</P>
<P>
Chris Haiveta, former deputy prime minister, who was criticized
by a judicial inquiry for the failed mercenary plan, was expected
to be a contender for the deputy prime ministership.
</P>
<P>
Chan's coalition suffered a major defeat in last month's
elections, with 15 ministers losing their seats in a voter
backlash against alleged political corruption and the mercenary
plan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
