<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Use Of Rainwater For Irrigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in north China's dry areas
are benefiting from a rainwater irrigation project that uses
cisterns to store rainwater for use during dry periods,
</P>
<P>
This project has proven effective in helping poor villagers
eliminate poverty.
</P>
<P>
Gansu Province in northwest China began using the method in
1995, and since then has applied it to some 13,000 ha of farmland
last year. It plans to use it on another 33,000 ha this year
and 166,000 ha by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the use of rainwater doubled per-unit wheat output
in the central mountainous part of the province, greatly
encouraging local farmers, who had long been plagued by water
shortages. Now they are all busy building rainwater storage
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The province had a record grain harvest last year and more than
a million farmers became better off. The rainwater project was said
to have contributed considerably to this. This year, the
facilities will mainly be built in poor mountainous areas to help
the remaining 3.7 million poor people.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has decided to provide 3,000 yuan per
ha in subsidies for rainwater-irrigated land, to help the 10
million farmers in dry areas in central and eastern parts of the
province to have a certain amount of farmland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
