<HEADLINE> Anglo American Firm to Tap Nickel-Cobalt In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Anglo
American Corporation has signed a joint venture pact with Sutto
Resources Limited (T), having acquired a 60 percent shares in
Kabanga Nickel Company in Ngara district, northwestern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to local press today, The agreement was signed
between Anglo Head of New Mining Business Division, Rober Danchin
and Sutton's Chairman Roman Shklanka in Dodoma, Central Tanzania
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, Anglo would undertake a program of
additional exploration drilling at the Kabanga nickel-cobalt
project and complete a feasibility study within four years.
</P>
<P>
Danchin said at the signing ceremony that he was optimistic
that the program of exploration and drilling would be conducted
over the next 18 months and would provide the necessary basis for
establishment of a mine and treatment facility at Kabanga.
</P>
<P>
"We the two partners hope our joint efforts will help to
stimulate the development of the project area and contribute to
Tanzania's economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Shklanka said the two firms were looking forward
to seeing the project reach maturity.
</P>
<P>
Kabanga forms part of a belt of nickel-ferrousa mineralization
stretching from the Ugandan border in the north to the shores of
Lake Tanganyika in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Currently identified resources at Kabanga amount to
approximately 20 million tons at grades of 1.65 percent nickel
and 0.14 percent cobalt.
</P>
<P>
An initial appraisal study identified a viable resource of
massive sulphide mineralization consisting of 12.7 million tons
at grades of 2.1 percent nickel and 0.16 percent cobalt.
</P>
<P>
Anglo's Divisional Communications Manager Msekiwa Kumbula said
that his firm would contribute 27 million U.S. Dollars toward
development of the project.
</P>
<P>
He said the total capital investment to establish a mine and
associated facilities at Kabanga was estimated at 135 million
U.S. Dollars. Full production was scheduled for 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
