<HEADLINE> U.S. to Train Ugandan Soldiers for Peace-keeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The 800-men Ugandan unit to be
trained by the United States "green beret" soldiers is a force
for disaster responding and traditionally peace keeping, Uganda's
army commander has said.
</P>
<P>
Major General Mugisha Muntu told local English newspaper "The
Crusader" last night that the unit to be trained by the U.S.
soldiers is not an elite commando force, adding, "they'll just be
trained in peace-keeping, not combat."
</P>
<P>
He made the explanation to the newspaper under widespread
speculation that the unit is to be trained as an elite commando
force to defend the country.
</P>
<P>
The Americans are not carrying into the country any
sophisticated equipment such as fighter planes, Muntu noted.
</P>
<P>
Fifty Americans started to arrive here yesterday and will
train the 800 Ugandan unit in Kabamba barracks in Mubende
District, central Uganda, the general disclosed.
</P>
<P>
He added that the training will last three months instead of
two months as reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan unit is part of eight to 10 African battalions to
be trained by Americans for peace-keeping purpose under the
auspices of the Organization of African Unity (OAU). Other units
are from Ethiopia, Ghana, Malawi, Mali and Senegal. 
</P>
