<HEADLINE> Developing Sericulture In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region is set to build a 6,600-hectare sericulture base
by the year 2000 as a means of improving the lives of local
farmers.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has listed sericulture as one of its
ten pillar industries for rural development and a key poverty
reduction program since 1989. Governments at various levels have
worked out preferential policies like loan guarantees, technical
training programs, and free mulberries seedlings to help with
this.
</P>
<P>
Some poverty-stricken counties in the Xihaigu area, one of the
poorest areas in the country, have improved farmers' living
standards by growing mulberries on a large scale. As a result, a
mulberry grower can earn 22,500 yuan annually from each ha of land.
</P>
<P>
Many counties have also established special funds and research
institutes to offer technical guidance.
</P>
<P>
The region's mulberry fields have by now grown to 1,333 ha and
have an annual output of 168 tons of silkworm cocoons. A local
official in charge of mulberry production and sericulture says
that the region will increase its annual output of raw silk to 800
tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
