<HEADLINE> Asia's Largest Coal Bins In North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Two bins for storing coal, 40m in
diameter and 54m deep with a 60,000-ton storage capacity each,
have been completed at the Yungang Mine in Shanxi Province in
north China.
</P>
<P>
The two bins signal a shift at Yungang Coal Mine, which is
directly under the jurisdiction of Datong Coal Mining
Administration.
</P>
<P>
The Yungang Coal Mine was designed and built by China, with a
designed annual production capacity of 2.7 million tons of
coal. In the past 20 years, it had produced 78 million tons of
coal and generated 1.11 billion yuan in pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
It was designated as a coal exporter in 1990. In recent years,
the mine decided to build a coal dressing plant as a way to
improve coal quality.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the coal dressing plant began in August of
1992 with an estimated cost at 302 million yuan. The 1.17-hectare
plant will be able to wash four million tons of coal and provide
three million tons of quality coal for export annually.  
</P>
