<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Formulate Mediation Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- China is mulling a law on
mediation in an effort to expand such a practice in solving civil
cases without going to court, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"Mediation, already an important method of avoiding costly
court hearings in Chinese civil cases, may be expanded through a
mediation law expected to come out in a few years," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Justice has drafted a law on the people's
mediation work and will submit it to the Legislative Bureau of the
State Council for examination by the end of this year, an official
with the ministry's Grassroots Work Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The law is expected to be discussed by the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress in a year or two, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mediation allows disputing parties to settle their
disagreements with the help and co-ordination of mediators. This
will keep the disputes from escalating into more severe situations
that end with the parties going to court.
</P>
<P>
The justice official said that the mediation system is "an
important part of the legal system with Chinese characteristics
that enjoys prestige worldwide."
</P>
<P>
The mediation law needs to cover many difficult subjects, the
official noted, including the legal status of mediation, the
validity of mediation agreements, rights and procedures of
handling civil disputes by grassroots mediation organizations and
funds for mediation.
</P>
<P>
To date, there are 1 million mediation organizations and more
than 10 million mediators across the country, and about 6 million
civil disputes of various kinds are mediated each year.
</P>
<P>
That is twice as many as first hearings of civil cases handled
by Chinese courts each year.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 civil disputes are resolved and prevented
from being intensified through mediation each year, the ministry
official said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that mediation has made important contributions
to maintaining social stability, safeguarding economic development
and promoting legislation in china.
</P>
<P>
But lack of a comprehensive law covering mediation does not fit
the rapid development of the work and the important role it has
played, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
