<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland to Rebuild Flood-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Polish government has launched
a long-term plan to rebuild the country's water infrastructure and
improve its water control system following the devastating floods
which hit the country this month, leaving 51 people dead and
64,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
The project, announced by the government today, consists of
three major steps.
</P>
<P>
First, immediate action will be taken by the government to
ensure people in flood-stricken areas have adequate housing and
children can go back to school before winter.
</P>
<P>
The second step aims at rebuilding infrastructure damaged by
the widespread flooding. The final step involves enlarging and
modernizing the country's reservoir system and rebuilding river
courses.
</P>
<P>
The plan was drawn up in the wake of torrential rain which has
caused widespread flooding across Poland over the last fortnight,
affecting 25 of the country's 47 provinces.
</P>
<P>
More than 1500 roads have been damaged, and 547,000 hectares of
farm land are under water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
