<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Kim Jongil, leader of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea, has stressed that his
country's position on the development of relations with the United
States and Japan remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The statement contained in a letter by Kim on July 13 to Mun
Myongja, a Korean-American woman journalist accredited to the
White House, who went to the DPRK to commemorate the third
anniversary of the death of DPRK President Kim Il Sung.
</P>
<P>
"In our relations with the United States, we will faithfully
implement the agreed points in conformity with the idea and
principle of our foreign policy," Kim said, adding "this is our
invariable stand," the Korean Central News Agency (KCNA) reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Our position for establishing good neighborhood and friendship
with Japan is also consistent," Kim said. "I think the settlement
of the issues depends on the attitude of the United States and
Japan toward us," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kim said in the letter that in spite of the repeated natural
disasters which had hit the country, he and his people were firmly
resolved to make the country ever more prosperous, the KCNA
reported. 
