<HEADLINE> Echoes From Mercosur Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items from the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) countries in
the past few days.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Economic performance in Argentina set a new
record in the first half of this year, 5 percent more than the
highest 1994 figure and 7 percent more than the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Between January and June of this year, the automobile sector
increased by 41 percent over the first six months of 1996,
followed by cement 32 percent and aluminum 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean and Argentine foreign and defence ministers
met here on July 16-17 to discuss regional security, cooperation,
the weaponry renewal process and the progress in settling their
border dispute over the southern ice fields.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The heads of the police investigation teams
from the four Mercosur member countries: Brazil, Argentina,
Uruguay and Paraguay, held a meeting on July 18 to exchange
information and experience to confront criminal gangs.
</P>
<P>
They exchanged confidential lists of 50 persons suspected to
have robbed several banks in the region.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Mercosur and Andean Group representatives have
made progress in their negotiations to create a free trade zone in
the next 10 years, though discrepancies also remain in several
topics.
</P>
<P>
The delegates from the two blocs agreed to exchange the lists
of products that will be included in the tariff-reduction program.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's trade inside the Mercosur rose to 2.7
billion U.S. dollars in the fiscal year ending in March with an
increase of 18.8 percent compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's trade with the three other Mercosur countries reached
1.6 billion dollars, 17.1 percent more than the year before and
Argentina 1.02 billion dollars with a growth of 19.3 percent
compared with the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Mercosur countries are improving their control
and supervision of border areas, local press reports said.
</P>
<P>
The security agreement signed a few weeks ago for the common
border areas includes the exchange of information among the police
of the four Mercosur members to fight against the organized
crimes, such as drug trafficking, arms peddling and money
laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
