<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Moves to Cut Birth Defects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province will
launch a health-promotion campaign in a bid to reduce incidence of
birth defects, a disease causing infant death and poor quality of
population.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government will allocate a special budget of
eight million yuan (963,000 US dollars) in the next four years to
down the incidence to half that of the year 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of counties of Shanxi will set up networks
to carry out pre-marital health examinations and provide medical
care for pregnant and lying-in women, according to a report in
today's Beijing-based "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The province has reported about 180 newly-borns among every
10,000 suffering from neural tube defects, which refer mainly to
babies born with no brains or with an exposed spine. Most infants
with such defects are born dead or die within a year.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi's incidence of birth defects is the highest not only in
China, but also in the entire world, China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
China has the highest incidence of neural tube defects in the
world, with some 80,000 to 100,000 cases a year - one-third of the
world's total, it said.
</P>
<P>
Health experts believed that the disease is closely related to
shortage of B-group vitamins and folic acid, known to be essential
to baby's development.
</P>
<P>
An investigation into diets for pregnant women conducted by the
China Medical University showed that an average 30 percent of
Chinese women of reproductive age suffer from vitamin B deficiency.
</P>
<P>
The research also found that if a woman takes about 0.4
milligrams of vitamin B supplements daily after marriage and until
her third month of pregnancy, the incidence of neural tube defects
is reduced 70 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
