<HEADLINE> Trial against Grobbelaar Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The trial for the alleged soccer
match-fixing, involving Zimbabwean Bruce Grobbelaar, was adjourned
on Monday as "no evidence" was found against him.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Banks, goalie for England's World Cup-winning team, told
the trial that he had seen videos of games highlighted in the case
and there was "not a scrap of evidence" to suggest that Grobbelaar
had fixed the games.
</P>
<P>
Grobbelaar, former Liverpool and Southampton keeper, had played
in a thoroughly professional and competent manner, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the trial, Grobbelaar also won support from former
England captain Jimmy Armfield and from former World Cup player
Alan Ball.
</P>
<P>
Ball, manager of Southampton who signed Grobbelaar at the start
of the 1994 season, spoke of his admiration for Grobbelaar and
described how he had continued to pick him after the match-fixing
allegations were first made in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution alleged that Grobbelaar, together with three
others, was part of a plot involving a Far Eastern betting
syndicate to rig the results of Premier League games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
