<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Increase In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Imports and exports of east China's
Shandong Province continued to grow in the first six months of the
year, with a total volume of 8.5 billion U.S. dollars, a 20
percent rise over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
During that time, Shandong has intensified reforms in its foreign
trade sector, using takeovers, bankruptcies and reshuffling of
assets for a group of small debt-ridden foreign trade
companies. And more than 200 foreign trade enterprises in the
province have incorporated and issued shares.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade enterprises have gone from small, scattered
businesses to united ones through structural adjustments, and more
than 20 foreign trade conglomerates have been formed in the
province.
</P>
<P>
The province has strengthened its export market in Europe, the
United States, and Japan and has redoubled efforts to explore new
markets in Southeast Asia, South Asia, Latin America, and Africa
since the beginning of the year. It has established economic and
trade relations with more than 180 countries, and there is a sharp
increase of new businessmen coming from Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the province's entire foreign trade sector
had improved its performance and reported a profit after losing
about 200 million U.S. dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
