<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiger Park Fascinates Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Thirty Siberian tigers are now
feeling at home in the world's largest forest-based tiger park in
Harbin, capital city of Heilongjiang Province in Northeast China.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, since the park opened in
January, over 200,000 people, including 20,000 from abroad, have
visited the park to enjoy the majestic Siberian tigers.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xinchen, manager of the park, says that the tigers, whose
ancestors roamed the earth one million years earlier than man, are
living mainly in Northeast China and Siberia.
</P>
<P>
There are now less than 300 wild Siberian tigers in the world;
In China, the number of the tigers in the wild stands at around
20, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
China founded a Siberian tiger breeding base in 1986 to
increase the number of the endangered beast. The base has bred 88
tigers so far and has become the biggest tiger-breeding base in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Last January, an area in the park was set up to copy the
tigers' natural habitat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0255 </DOCNO>
