<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Treasurer Peter Costello conceded last night a
top-secret Australian report on the South Pacific was "very deeply
insulting" but refused to make a formal apology to regional
politicians subject to extraordinary personal criticisms. The
leaked 93-page report criticized some South Pacific island
countries and their leaders for economic mismanagement and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Fears that Sydney is losing its race with Melbourne have
driven a business group to set up a committee to crash through
where bureaucracies have failed to plan, promote and protect the
city. The committee is to be launched by the state government
where the city is located with an agenda ranging from urban
planning and tourism to the arts and law and order.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The hearing ability of Australian children is likely to
decline quicker than that of their parents because of pop music,
noisy films and head injuries, a new study shows. The National
Acoustic Laboratories study of 2,500 people from birth to old age
has also found that boys are faring worse than girls.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The six-week strike at resource giant Rio Tinto's Hunter
Valley mine is set to end from midnight tonight after the union
backed down in a dispute that had threatened to escalate into a
national stoppage. But Australia's biggest coal port has now been
affected by industrial action, with maritime unions imposed bans
and limitations on coal movements from Newcastle and threatening
full-scale stoppages that would disrupt coal exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
