<HEADLINE> Pangalos: Madrid Communique Enables Direct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos has hailed the recent joint communique signed between
Greece and Turkey in Madrid as a major political development that
created a new situation and brought about their direct talks on
bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
According to the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) today,
speaking in an interview with the Athens daily The News, Pangalos
said that Greece and Turkey would meet in November on the Greek
island of Crete on the sidelines of the summit meeting of European
countries.
</P>
<P>
As for the possibility of top-level Greek-Turkish meetings, he
said, "We now have this possibility and this is the major gain
from Madrid."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that although Washington continued its contacts
with both Athens and Ankara, he believed that the next initiative
should come from the two countries themselves.
</P>
<P>
He called on Ankara to abandon its past and look to the future,
noting that Athens would follow such an effort with a sincere
desire to help. 
</P>
