<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USS Constitution Sails After 116 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The USS Constitution, the
wooden sailing ship that defended the United States during the War
of 1812 with Britain, today set sail for the first time in 116
years in Massachusetts Bay.
</P>
<P>
It set sail today for its 200th birthday. The sails were the
same configuration the 204-foot ship used in battle.
</P>
<P>
The wind was from the southwest at up to 14 knots in
Massachusetts Bay, pleasant for sailing.
</P>
<P>
Aboard for the historic cruise were politicians, military
officers and sailors formerly assigned to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 100,000 people, on land and on sea, watched as the
ship was towed out to open sea today from Marblehead, where it
spent the night after being brought from its berth in Boston
Harbor.
</P>
<P>
Launched as one of the U.S. Navy's first warships, the ship,
Old Ironsides, was undefeated in 30 engagements. Its victory over
the HMS Guerriere in 1812 signaled America's birth of naval power.
</P>
<P>
The ship's most famous visit to Marblehead Harbor came on April
3, 1814, when it sought shelter from two 38-gun British frigates.
With nearly a third of its crew from Marblehead, the Constitution
had little problem navigating the narrow channel into the harbor.
The British ships wouldn't risk the unfamiliar water.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of the ship's parts has taken three and a half
years.
</P>
<P>
Constitution's last free sail was in 1881. It visited ports on
both coasts in the early 1930s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Urges Canada to End Blockade in Salmon Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. today urged the
Canadian authorities to end a blockade of a U.S. Alaska's ferry by
Canadian fisherman.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has protested and continues to protest this
blockade," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"We also protest the refusal of Canadian federal authorities to
stop the blockade or to enforce the court injunction. Canada must
take action to enforce the court's judgment," he added.
</P>
<P>
Angered by allegations that Alaskan fishermen were taking more
than double their normal catch of salmon so far this year,
Canadian fishermen today continued for the third day their
blockade of the Alaska state ferry off Canada's British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
"The Canadian government has not enforced that injunction,
neither the provincial officials in British Columbia, nor the
federal officials in Ottawa," Burns added.
</P>
<P>
"The blockade harms innocent people who have nothing to do with
the salmon fishery," Burns said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
