<HEADLINE> Israel's Official to Be in Washington on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel's cabinet secretary
Danny Naveh is coming to Washington to hold talks with U.S.
mediator Dennis Ross, seeking a way out of the current stalemate
in the Middle East peace process, the State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to talking to him. We are trying to be
an effective mediator," spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
His visit followed the one by chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erakat who held talks with Ross and other senior department
officials last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Erakat urged the Clinton administration to devise a new
strategy to revive negotiations between Israel and the
Palestinians or face the prospect of disaster in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
But the United States urged the two sides to revitalize their
negotiations by themselves, and Washington first has to "listen to
their ideas how the peace process can move forward," U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Burns told reporters the main objective of the Clinton
administration through talks with both the Israelis and
Palestinians "is to promote the willingness of the two sides to
move forward."
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between the Israelis and Palestinians
have run aground for several months since the Israeli government,
in defiance to peace accords signed by both sides, decided in
March to build new Jewish housing units in traditionally Arab east
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The United States has given only lip criticism on Israel's move
and, meanwhile, criticized the Palestinians for their protests
against Israel's construction plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
