<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Criticizes Statements by Turkish Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece today criticized Turkish
Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's statements made Sunday on
Turkey's partial integration process with northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Greece's government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today that
Ecevit's statements were "completely inopportune, incompatible
with efforts for a settlement of the Cyprus problem and
inconsistent with Turkey's effort to come closer to the European
Union (EU)."
</P>
<P>
"Such behavior compromises Turkey and is seen by the
international community as belonging to the past," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU had fixed in the most official and
categorical manner the timetable for accession negotiations with
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Reppas warned that Greece wanted calm and stability in the
region but at the same time it was ready to confront any
phenomenon and was on alert.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, who as prime minister ordered the 1974 Turkish invasion
of Cyprus, attended the 23rd anniversary ceremony in the northern
part of the island Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit reportedly claimed that integration with Turkey of the
self-proclaimed Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, recognized
only by Ankara, was inevitable after last week's confirmation by
the EU that Nicosia was among the countries who would start the
accession negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Turkish Cyprus regime in the north would
live forever as "an independent state," but its foreign policy and
defense would be handled by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied northern Cyprus in the wake of a Greek Cypriot coup
engineered by the then ruling military junta in Greece.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Ruaf Denktash held their first face-to-face talks in three
years in Troutbeck, near New York, in a bid to seek solutions to
the Cyprus problem. The two also have agreed to hold their second
round of talks in Switzerland in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
