<DOCNO> XIE19970722.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, World Largest Importer of Farm Products in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite a slight drop in imports,
Germany was still the world largest importer of farm products in
1996, taking in nearly 10 percent of farm goods traded on the
world market, the German Ministry of Agriculture said today.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by the ministry in Bonn today,
Germany's farm imports dropped by 0.5 percent to 67.8 billion
marks (37.9 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996 while exports climbed
nearly 4 percent to a new record of 39.5 billion marks (22.1
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The export boom, which was attributed to the weak German mark
and the fast-growing demand from central and eastern European
countries, had helped reduce the country's trade surplus in the
agricultural sector by 1.7 billion marks (950 million dollars) to
28.3 billion marks (15.8 billion dollars) last year, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union was still Germany's largest market, which
absorbed about two thirds of the country's farm exports, followed
by central and eastern Europe where Germany's farm exports soared
23 percent to 6 billion marks (3.4 billion dollars) last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
